# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: allendism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The **1973 Chilean coup d'état** (Spanish: *Golpe de Estado en Chile de 1973*) was a military overthrow of the socialist president of Chile Salvador Allende and his Popular Unity coalition government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende, who has been described as the first Marxist to be democratically elected president in a Latin American liberal democracy, faced significant social unrest and political tension with the opposition-controlled National Congress of Chile.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On 11 September 1973, a group of military officers, led by General Augusto Pinochet, seized power in a coup, ending civilian rule.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] During the air raids and ground attacks preceding the coup, Allende delivered his final speech, expressing his determination to remain at Palacio de La Moneda and rejecting offers of safe passage for exile.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The exact circumstances of Allende's death are still disputed, but it is generally accepted as a suicide.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Following the coup, a military junta was established and it suspended all political activities in Chile and suppressed left-wing movements, such as the Communist Party of Chile and the Socialist Party of Chile, the Revolutionary Left Movement (MIR), and other communist and socialist parties.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Pinochet swiftly consolidated power and was officially declared president of Chile in late 1974.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Nixon administration, which had played a role in creating favorable conditions for the coup, promptly recognized the junta government and supported its efforts to consolidate power.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In 2023, declassified documents showed that Nixon, Henry Kissinger, and the United States government, which had described Allende as a dangerous communist, were aware of the military's plans to overthrow Allende in the days before the coup d'état.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] According to historian Sebastián Hurtado Torres, there is no documentary evidence to support that the United States government acted actively in the coordination and execution of the coup actions by the Chilean Armed Forces.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] However, Richard Nixon's interest from the beginning was that the Allende government would not be consolidated.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Historian Peter Winn found "extensive evidence" of United States complicity in events that helped in part to create the conditions that led to the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Fidel Castro's Cuba was allied with the Allende Government, providing weapons to Left-Wing groups in Chile and Cuban officials tried to convince Allende to make a coup before the opposition made one.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Castro visited Chile in 1971 staying for 24 days, more than initially expected.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The KGB considered Allende a "confidential contact" according to the Mitrokhin Archive.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Chile had previously been regarded as a symbol of democracy and political stability in South America, while other countries in the region suffered under military juntas and *caudillismo*.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The period in Chile before the coup is known as the Presidential Republic (1925–1973) era.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] At the time, Chile was a middle-class country, with about 30% or 9 million Chileans being middle class.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The collapse of Chilean democracy marked the end of a series of democratic governments that had held elections since 1932.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Historian Peter Winn described the 1973 coup as one of the most violent events in Chilean history.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The coup led to a series of human rights abuses in Chile under Pinochet, who initiated a brutal and long-lasting campaign of political suppression through torture, murder, and exile, which significantly weakened leftist opposition to the military dictatorship of Chile (1973–1990).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Nonetheless, Pinochet stepped down from power voluntarily after the internationally supported 1988 referendum about his continuity and the 1989 constitutional reform referendum held under the military junta led to the peaceful transition to democracy.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Due to the coup's coincidental occurrence on the same date as the 11 September 2001 attacks in the United States, it has sometimes been referred to as "the other 9/11".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende contested the 1970 Chilean presidential election with Jorge Alessandri Rodríguez of the National Party and Radomiro Tomic of the Christian Democratic Party.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende received 36.6% of the vote, while Alessandri was a very close second with 35.3%, and Tomic third with 28.1%, in what was a close three-way election.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Although Allende received the highest number of votes, according to the Chilean constitution and since none of the candidates won by an absolute majority, the National Congress had to decide among the candidates.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Chilean Constitution of 1925 did not allow a person to serve consecutive terms as president.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The incumbent president, Eduardo Frei Montalva, was therefore ineligible to run.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The CIA's "Track I" operation was a plan to influence Congress to choose Alessandri, who would resign after a short time in office, forcing a second election.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Alessandri announced on 9 September that if Congress chose him, he would resign.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende signed the Statute of Constitutional Guarantees, which stated that he would abide by the constitution during his presidency, in an effort to shore up support for his candidacy.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The U.S. feared the example of a "well-functioning socialist experiment" in the region and exerted diplomatic, economic, and covert pressure upon Chile's elected socialist government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] At the end of 1971, the Cuban Prime Minister Fidel Castro made a four-week state visit to Chile, alarming American observers worried about the "Chilean Way to Socialism".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The documents also claim that the Soviet intelligence service sought closer cooperation between Chilean intelligence agencies and the Soviet Union, including a possible reorganization of the Chilean Army and intelligence services, proposals to which Allende allegedly reacted positively.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The KGB reportedly viewed the Popular Unity government's situation as increasingly difficult by 1972 and criticized Allende for not using "force" against his opponents.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] After the 1973 Chilean coup d'état, Soviet intelligence officials reportedly complained that Allende had given little importance to their warnings about the possibility of his overthrow.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende presided over an increasingly unstable economy.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In 1972, Economics Minister Pedro Vuskovic adopted monetary policies that increased the amount of circulating currency and devalued the escudo.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] That year, inflation increased by 225% and reached 606% by 1973.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The high inflation in 1973 decreased wages by 38%.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] To combat this, Allende created the Committees of Supplies and Prices (Juntas de Abastecimiento y Precios (JAP)).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] JAP reopened private shops and requisitioned goods that had been slowly disappearing due to declining production.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In October 1972, Chile suffered the first of many strikes.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Trucker's Strike that began on 1 October in Aysen province was a response to economic problems and rumors of transportation nationalization.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Eight days later, the Confederation of Truckers, led by Leon Vilarín and supported by the guilds and possibly the CIA, called for an indefinite national strike, which further hindered the movement and distribution of goods that were already struggling.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Truckers then blocked all main roads on 12 October, creating a shortage of essential goods.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende declared a state of emergency in response, and the strike leaders were arrested.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] This would only further provoke the Chilean population, and more strikes and protests ensued.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The state of emergency also failed to reverse the strike or the economic crisis.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Among the participants were small-scale businesspeople, some professional unions, and student groups.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Its leaders – Vilarín, Jaime Guzmán, Rafael Cumsille, Guillermo Elton, Eduardo Arriagada – expected to depose the elected government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Other than damaging the national economy, the principal effect of the 24-day strike was drawing Army head, General Carlos Prats, into the government as Interior Minister, an appeasement to the right wing.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Despite the declining economy, President Allende's Popular Unity coalition increased its vote to 43.2% in the March 1973 parliamentary elections; but, by then, the informal alliance between Popular Unity and the Christian Democrats ended.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Christian Democrats allied with the right-wing National Party, who were opposed to Allende's government; the two right-wing parties formed the Confederation of Democracy (CODE).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The internecine conflict between the legislature and the executive branch paralyzed government operations.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende began to fear his opponents, convinced they were plotting his assassination.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Using his daughter Beatriz as a messenger, he explained the situation to Fidel Castro.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende attempted to follow Castro's advice, but the latter two recommendations proved difficult to implement.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Before the coup, the Chilean military had undergone a process of depoliticization since the 1920s, when military officers had held cabinet positions.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Subsequently, most military officers remained underfunded, having only subsistence salaries.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Because of low salaries, the military spent much of their time in military leisure facilities (e.g., country clubs) where they met other officers and their families.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The military remained apart from society and was, to some degree, an endogamous group, as officers frequently married the sisters of their comrades or the daughters of high-ranking older officers.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Many officers also had relatives in the military.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In 1969, elements of the military made their first act of rebellion in 40 years when they participated in the Tacnazo insurrection.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Tacnazo was not a proper coup, but a protest against under-funding.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In retrospect, General Carlos Prats considered that Christian Democrats, who were in power in 1969, committed the error of not taking the military's grievances seriously.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the governments of Ecuador (1963), Brazil (1964), Argentina (1966), Peru (1968), and Bolivia (1969) were overthrown and replaced by military governments.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In June 1973, Uruguay joined the coup d'état wave that swept through the region.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The poor conditions of the Chilean military contrasted with the change of fortune the military of neighboring countries experienced as they came to power in coups.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] During the decades before the coup, the military became influenced by the United States' anti-communist ideology in the context of various cooperation programs, including the U.S.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On 29 June 1973, Colonel Roberto Souper surrounded La Moneda presidential palace with his tank regiment and failed to depose the Allende Government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] That failed *coup d'état* – known as the *Tanquetazo* tank putsch – had been organized by the nationalist "Fatherland and Liberty" paramilitary group.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In August 1973, a constitutional crisis occurred; the Supreme Court publicly complained about the government's inability to enforce the law of the land.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On 22 August, the Christian Democrats united with the National Party of the Chamber of Deputies accused the government of unconstitutional acts and called upon the military to enforce constitutional order.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On August 21, both Tomé and Concepción saw large demonstrations, prompting the Chilean Army and Navy to occupy the two cities.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The occupation lasted three weeks, culminating in the assault of the presidential palace, La Moneda, in Santiago.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] For months, the government had feared calling upon the *Carabineros* national police, suspecting them of disloyalty.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On 9 August, Allende appointed General Carlos Prats as Minister of Defense.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] He was forced to resign as both defense minister and Army commander-in-chief on 24 August 1973, embarrassed by the Alejandrina Cox incident and by a public protest by the wives of his generals at his house.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] General Augusto Pinochet replaced him as Army commander-in-chief the same day.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In late August 1973, 100,000 Chilean women congregated at Plaza de la Constitución to protest against the government for the rising cost and increasing shortages of food and fuels, but they were dispersed with tear gas.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Essentially, most of the accusations were about the government disregarding the separation of powers and arrogating legislative and judicial prerogatives to the executive branch.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Finally, the resolution condemned the "creation and development of government-protected armed groups, which ... are headed towards a confrontation with the armed forces".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] President Allende's efforts to reorganize the military and the police forces were characterized as "notorious attempts to use the armed and police forces for partisan ends, destroy their institutional hierarchy, and politically infiltrate their ranks".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The resolution was later used by Pinochet as a way to justify the coup, which occurred two weeks later.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On 24 August 1973, two days after the resolution, Allende responded.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] He accused the opposition of trying to incite a military coup by encouraging the armed forces to disobey civilian authorities.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende argued that he had obeyed constitutional means in including military men in the cabinet to serve civic peace and national security, defending republican institutions against insurrection and terrorism.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] He further argued that the legislature was usurping the government's executive function.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende wrote: "Chilean democracy is a conquest by all of the people.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] It is neither the work nor the gift of the exploiting classes, and it will be defended by those who, with sacrifices accumulated over generations, have imposed it ...
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] I sustain that never before has Chile had a more democratic government than that over which I have the honor to preside ...
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] I solemnly reiterate my decision to develop democracy and a state of law to their ultimate consequences ...
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] He concluded by calling upon the workers and all democrats and patriots to join him in defending the Chilean constitution and the revolutionary process.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Southern Pacific Nautical Brotherhood was an important nucleus in the conspiracy to organize the coup d'état against Salvador Allende.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] All its members would later occupy important positions in the de facto government, both within it and from outside it.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The meetings were held as rotating dinners in the homes of each member.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] All members, both civilians and military officers, took an active role in the sedition against the government of Salvador Allende, in the preparation of the coup, and during the dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In mid-July, a month before the resolution of the Chamber of Deputies, there was general agreement in the heart of the Army's high command on the desirability of terminating the Unidad Popular "experiment." How to do it was still nebulous.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The constitutional generals, gathered around Army Commander-in-Chief General Carlos Prats, were facing pressure from an increasingly hardline anti-Allende faction within the Army.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Prats had proposed an Allende–Armed Forces government, including a "political peace treaty" with the Christian Democrats and restricted participation by the Chilean Communist Party and a group of Socialists.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Many people in different parts of the world immediately suspected the U.S. of foul play.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In early newspaper reports, the U.S. denied any involvement or previous knowledge of the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Prompted by an incriminating *New York Times* article, the U.S.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Senate opened an investigation into U.S. interference in Chile.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Historian Peter Winn found "extensive evidence" of United States complicity in creating the conditions prior to the coup during Allende's rule.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] He states that the covert support to the political opposition was crucial to engineering the coup by the Chilean Armed Forces and to consolidating power by the Pinochet regime following the takeover.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Winn documents an extensive CIA operation to fabricate reports of a coup against Allende, as justification for the imposition of military rule.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Peter Kornbluh asserts that the CIA destabilized Chile and helped create the conditions for the coup, citing documents declassified by the Clinton administration.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Other authors point to the involvement of the Defense Intelligence Agency, agents of which allegedly secured the missiles used to bombard the La Moneda Palace.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] As described in the Church Committee report, the CIA was involved in multiple plots designed to remove Allende and then let the Chileans vote in a new election where he would not be a candidate.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The first, non-military, approach involved attempting a constitutional coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] This was known as the Track I approach, in which the CIA, with the approval of the 40 Committee, attempted to bribe the Chilean legislature, tried to influence public opinion against Allende, and provided funding to strikes designed to coerce him into resigning.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] It also attempted to have Congress confirm Jorge Alessandri as the winner of the presidential election.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Alessandri, who was an accessory to the conspiracy, was ready to resign then and call for fresh elections.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] This approach completely failed in 1970 and was not attempted again.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The other CIA approach in 1970 (but not later), also known as the Track II approach, sought to encourage a military coup by creating a climate of crisis across the country.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] False flag operatives contacted senior Chilean military officers and informed them that the U.S. would actively support a coup but would revoke all military aid if it did not occur.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In addition, the CIA gave extensive support for black propaganda against Allende, channeled mostly through *El Mercurio*.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Financial assistance was also given to Allende's political opponents to organize strikes and unrest to destabilize the government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] By 1970, the U.S. manufacturing company ITT Corporation owned 70% of Chitelco (the Chilean Telephone Company), and also funded *El Mercurio*.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The CIA used ITT as a means of disguising the source of the illegitimate funding Allende's opponents received.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On 28 September 1973, the Weather Underground bombed ITT's headquarters in New York City in retaliation.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] According to an article written by lifelong CIA operative Jack Devine, although it was widely reported that the CIA was directly involved in orchestrating and carrying out the coup, subsequently released sources suggest a much-reduced role of the US government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] By 6:00 am on 11 September 1973, a date chosen to match a historical 1924 coup, the Navy captured Valparaíso, strategically stationing ships and marine infantry in the central coast and closing radio and television networks.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Province Prefect informed President Allende of the Navy's actions; immediately, the president went to the presidential palace (La Moneda) with his bodyguards, the "Group of Personal Friends" (GAP).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] By 8:00 a.m., the Army had closed most radio and television stations in Santiago city, one of the first acts of the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] By 8.30 a.m., both the carabineros and the military broadcast their first edict, which would present a unified front to dispose of Allende.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Air Force bombed the remaining active stations, and the President received incomplete information that convinced him that only a sector of the Navy conspired against him and his government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] President Allende and Defense Minister Orlando Letelier were unable to communicate with military leaders.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The military would arrest Orlando Letelier upon reaching the Defense Ministry.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Following this, he would be imprisoned, then exiled and assassinated in Washington D.C. on 21 September 1976.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] There is evidence that Pinochet ordered his assassination.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Admiral Montero, the Navy's commander and an Allende loyalist, was rendered incommunicado; his telephone service was cut, and his cars were sabotaged before the *coup d'état* to ensure he could not thwart the opposition.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Leadership of the Navy was transferred to José Toribio Merino, planner of the *coup d'état* and executive officer to Adm.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Augusto Pinochet, General of the Army, and Gustavo Leigh, General of the Air Force, did not answer Allende's telephone calls to them.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The General Director of the *Carabineros* (uniformed police), José María Sepúlveda, and the head of the Investigations Police (plain clothes detectives), Alfredo Joignant answered Allende's calls and immediately went to the *La Moneda* presidential palace.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Despite evidence that all branches of the Chilean armed forces were involved in the coup, Allende hoped that some units remained loyal to the government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende was convinced of Pinochet's loyalty, telling a reporter that the *coup d'état* leaders must have imprisoned the general.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Only at 8:30 am, when the armed forces declared control of Chile and deposed Allende, did the president grasp the magnitude of the military's rebellion.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Despite the lack of any military support, Allende refused to resign his office.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] 9:00 the carabineros of the La Moneda left the building.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] By 9:00 a.m., the armed forces controlled Chile, except for the city centre of the capital, Santiago.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Originally, the military had planned to arrest Allende at his residence, but he made it to *La Moneda,* the presidential palace.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] There, Allende refused to surrender, despite the military declaring they would bomb *La Moneda* if he resisted being deposed.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The military would turn to negotiating with Allende, offering to fly him and his family out of Chile, which Allende would refuse.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Socialist Party, along with his Cuban advisors, proposed to Allende that he escape to the San Joaquín industrial zone in southern Santiago, to later re-group and lead a counter-*coup d'état*; the president rejected the proposition.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] According to Tanya Harmer, Allende's refusal to lead an insurgency against the coup is evidence of his unrelenting desire to bring about change through non-violent methods.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Cuban embassy in Chile, located in the Providencia district, was surrounded by units of the Chilean Army.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] According to former Cuban official Max Marambio, Cuban representatives allegedly attempted to contact Salvador Allende to offer military support during the coup attempt against him, a proposal that the president reportedly declined.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The military attempted more negotiations with Allende.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Still, the President refused to resign, citing his constitutional duty to remain in office.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Finally, at 9:10 a.m., Allende gave a farewell speech, telling the nation of the *coup d'état* and his refusal to resign his elected office under threat.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Leigh ordered the presidential palace bombed but was told the Air Force's Hawker Hunter jet aircraft would take forty minutes to arrive from their base at Concepcion.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Pinochet ordered an armoured and infantry force under General Sergio Arellano to advance upon the *La Moneda* presidential palace.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] When the troops moved forward, they were forced to retreat after coming under fire from GAP snipers perched on rooftops.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] General Arellano called for helicopter gunship support from the commander of the Chilean Army Puma helicopter squadron and the troops were able to advance again.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Chilean Air Force aircraft soon arrived to provide close air support for the assault (by bombing the Palace), but the defenders did not surrender until nearly 2:30 pm.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende would be found in his inner office dead, from a self-inflicted bullet wound done between 2:00 and 2:30 p.m.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Before Allende's suicide, he addressed the nation one final time and stated hope for Chile in the future and wished for the people to stay strong-willed and overcome the darkness.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In his own words, he said: "Workers of my country, I have faith in Chile and its destiny.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Other men will overcome this dark and bitter moment when treason seeks to prevail.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Keep in mind that, much sooner than later, the great avenues will again be opened through which will pass free men to construct a better society.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Pinochet's rule would officially begin at 2:30 p.m.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] According to official reports prepared after the return of democracy, at La Moneda, only two people died: President Allende and the journalist Augusto Olivares (both by suicide).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Two more were injured, Antonio Aguirre and Osvaldo Ramos, both members of President Allende's entourage; they would later be allegedly kidnapped from the hospital and disappeared.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] In November 2006, the Associated Press noted that more than 15 bodyguards and aides were taken from the palace during the coup and are still unaccounted for; in 2006, Augusto Pinochet was indicted for two of their deaths.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On the military side, there were 34 deaths: two army sergeants, three army corporals, four army privates, two navy lieutenants, one navy corporal, four naval cadets, three navy conscripts and 15 carabineros.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] On 23 October 1973, 23-year-old army corporal Benjamín Alfredo Jaramillo Ruz, who was serving with the *Cazadores*, became the first fatal casualty of the counterinsurgency operations in the mountainous area of Alquihue in Valdivia after being shot by a sniper.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The Chilean Army suffered 12 killed in various clashes with MIR guerrillas and GAP fighters in October 1973.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] While fatalities in the battle during the coup might have been relatively small, the Chilean security forces sustained 162 dead in the three following months as a result of continued resistance, and tens of thousands of people were arrested during the coup and held in the National Stadium.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] An estimated 40,000 Chileans were tortured under the Pinochet regime in the years following the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] President Allende died in La Moneda during the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The junta officially declared that he committed suicide with a rifle given to him by Fidel Castro, two doctors from the infirmary of La Moneda stated that they witnessed the suicide, and an autopsy labelled Allende's death a suicide.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Vice Admiral Patricio Carvajal, one of the primary instigators of the coup, claimed that "Allende committed suicide and is dead now." Patricio Guijon, one of the president's doctors, had testified to witnessing Allende shoot himself under the chin with the rifle while seated on a sofa.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] At the time, few of Allende's supporters believed the explanation that Allende had killed himself.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The team was composed of international forensic experts to ensure an independent evaluation.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] However, on 31 May 2011, Chile's state television station reported that a top-secret military account of Allende's death had been discovered in the home of a former military justice official.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] The 300-page document was found only when the house was destroyed in the 2010 Chilean earthquake.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] After reviewing the report, two forensic experts told Televisión Nacional de Chile "that they are inclined to conclude that Allende was assassinated." Two forensics experts said they believed he was shot with a small-calibre weapon before the AK-47.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] One expert, Luis Ravanal, noted the lack of blood on his collar, sweater, and throat suggested someone else fired the AK-47 when he was already dead.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p01] Allende's widow and family escaped the military government and were granted asylum in Mexico, where they remained for 17 years.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] On 13 September, the Junta dissolved Congress, outlawed the parties that had been part of the Popular Unity coalition; all political activity was declared "in recess".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The military government took control of all media, including the radio broadcasting that Allende attempted to use to give his final speech to the nation.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] It is not known how many Chileans actually heard Allende's last words as he spoke them, but a transcript and audio of the speech survived the military government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Baltra details how the military took control of the media platforms and turned them into their own "propaganda machine".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The only two newspapers that were allowed to continue publishing after the military takeover were *El Mercurio* and *La Tercera de la Hora*, both of which were anti-Allende under his leadership.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The dictatorship's silencing of the leftist point of view extended past the media and into "every discourse that expressed any resistance to the regime".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] An example of this is the torturing and death of folk singer Víctor Jara.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The military government detained Jara in the days following the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] He, along with many other leftists, was held in Estadio Nacional, or the National Stadium of Chile, in the capital of Santiago.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Initially, the Junta tried to silence him by crushing his hands, but ultimately, he was murdered.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Immediately after the coup the military sought television host Don Francisco to have him report on the events.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Don Francisco declined the offer, encouraging the captain who had approached him to take the role of reporter himself.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Coup leaders soon decided against a rotating presidency and named General Pinochet permanent head of the junta which would establish a 17-year-long civil-military dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Historian Peter Winn states that the Central Intelligence Agency had an extensive part to play in fabricating the conspiracy and in selling it to the press, both in Chile and internationally.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Although later discredited and officially recognized as the product of political propaganda, Gonzalo Vial has pointed to the similarities between the alleged Plan Z and other existing paramilitary plans of the Popular Unity parties in support of its legitimacy.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] A document from September 13 shows that Jaime Guzmán was already, by then, tasked with studying the creation of a new constitution.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] One of the first measures of the dictatorship was to set up a Secretaría Nacional de la Juventud (SNJ, National Youth Office).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] This was done on 28 October 1973, even before the Declaration of Principles of the junta made in March 1974.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] This was a way of mobilizing sympathetic elements of the civil society in support of the dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] In the first months after the *coup d'état,* the military killed thousands of Chilean leftists, both real and suspected, or forced their "disappearance".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The military imprisoned 40,000 political enemies in the National Stadium of Chile; among the tortured and killed *desaparecidos* (disappeared) were the U.S. citizens Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] In September 1973, the Chilean songwriter Víctor Jara was murdered, along with 70 other people in a series of killings perpetrated by the death squad Caravan of Death (*Caravana de la Muerte*).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The government arrested some 130,000 people in a three-year period; the dead and disappeared numbered thousands in the first months of the military government.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] In Valparaiso, it is estimated that there were 6,918 victims of political capture and torture.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Those include the British physician Sheila Cassidy, who survived to publicize in the UK the human rights violations in Chile.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Among those detained was Alberto Bachelet (father of future Chilean President Michelle Bachelet), an Air Force official; he was tortured and died on 12 March 1974, the right-wing newspaper, *El Mercurio*, reported that Mr.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Bachelet died after a basketball game, citing his poor cardiac health.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Michelle Bachelet and her mother were imprisoned and tortured in the Villa Grimaldi detention and torture centre on 10 January 1975.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The newspaper *La Tercera* published on its front page a photograph showing prisoners at Quiriquina Island Camp who had been captured during the fighting in Concepción.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The photograph's caption stated that some of the detained were "local bosses of Unidad Popular" while others were "extremists who had attacked the armed forces with firearms".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] This is consistent with reports in newspapers and broadcasts in Concepción about the activities of the Armed Forces, which mentioned clashes with "extremists" on several occasions from 11 to 14 September.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Nocturnal skirmishes took place around the Hotel Alonso de Ercilla on Colo Colo and San Martín Streets, one block from the Army and military police administrative headquarters.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] A recently published testimony about the clashes in Concepción offers several plausible explanations for witnesses' reticence to report these actions.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Besides political leaders and participants, the coup also affected many everyday Chilean citizens.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Pinochet and the military junta proclaimed that they were going to get rid of "the cancerous tumor," in reference to Chile's left.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Thousands were killed, went missing, and were injured.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Thousands more emigrated or were exiled due to political instability in their regions, and many relocated elsewhere.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Canada, among other countries, became a major refuge for many Chilean citizens.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Through an operation known as "Special Movement Chile", more than 7,000 Chileans were relocated to Canada in the months following 11 September 1973.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] These refugees are now known as Chilean Canadian people and have a population of over 38,000.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Chileans would find asylum in over 40 countries around the world.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] While the exact number is unknown, it is estimated that at least 200,000 Chileans left Chile between 1973 and 1990, the largest flow of emigration in Chile's history.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Pinochet lost the election in the 1988 plebiscite, the Rettig Commission, a multi-partisan truth commission, in 1991 reported the location of torture and detention centers, among others, Colonia Dignidad, the tall ship *Esmeralda* and Víctor Jara Stadium.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Later, in November 2004, the Valech Report confirmed the number as fewer than 3,000 killed and reduced the number of cases of forced disappearance; but some 28,000 people were arrested, imprisoned, and tortured.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Sixty individuals died as a direct result of fighting on 11 September, although the MIR and GAP continued to fight the following day.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] It has been put forward that, in all, 46 of Allende's guard (the GAP, *Grupo de Amigos Personales*) were killed, some of them in combat with the soldiers that took the Moneda.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] However, a report of 1999 published by an organization of ex-GAP which survived the events around the coup d'état, says that no one among the GAP members were killed in La Moneda combat.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The source affirms that there were only 50 GAP members at that time.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The same information about the number of GAP members was later confirmed in an academic publication.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The U.S. view of the coup continues to spark controversy.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Beginning in late 2014 in response to a request by Senate Armed Services Committee Chair Carl Levin, United States Southern Command (USSOUTHCOM) William J.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Perry Center for Hemispheric Defense Studies (CHDS), located at the National Defense University in Washington, D.C., has been under investigation by the Department of Defense Office of Inspector General.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] "Reports that NDU hired foreign military officers with histories of involvement in human rights abuses, including torture and extrajudicial killings of civilians, are stunning, and they are repulsive", said Sen.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Patrick Leahy, D-Vermont, the author of the "Leahy Law" prohibiting U.S. assistance to military units and members of foreign security forces that violate human rights.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Roberto Thieme, the military leader of Fatherland and Liberty, who was imprisoned on 11 September, was shocked to hear about the degree of violence with which the coup was carried out.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Despite being an arduous opponent of Unidad Popular, he had expected a cleaner coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] President of Argentina Juan Domingo Perón condemned the coup, calling it a "fatality for the continent".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Before the coup Perón had warned the more radical of his followers to stay calm and "not do as Allende".
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Argentine students protested the coup at the Chilean embassy in Buenos Aires, where part of them chanted that they were "ready to cross the Andes" (*dispuestos a cruzar la cordillera*).
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] In fragmenting Francoist Spain, the coup came as a shock to the opposition many whom immediately identified the parallels between Francisco Franco and Pinochet and between the coup and the Spanish Civil War.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Since Spain was still under authoritarian rule the opposition was limited in its range of action.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The Spanish Socialist Workers' Party officially condemned the coup in its 1974 congress in France, and *Mundo Obrero* of the Communist Party of Spain called for resistance against the new regime.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Instead of radicalizing, the Chilean coup led the Spanish opposition to moderate its positions, as the socialist Enrique Tierno Galván would acknowledge.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Many cargo shipments involving trade with Cuba were affected by government policy decisions, and, subsequently, the performance of the trade contracts underlying the shipping deliveries was made illegal under Cuban law.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The Chilean company Iansa had purchased sugar from the Cuban business entity, Cubazukar.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Several shipments were at different stages of the shipping and delivery process.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The shipping contracts used the CIF trade terms.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The High Court (in England) ruled that IANSA was entitled to damages in respect of the undelivered balance of the *Playa Larga* cargo and to restitution of the price paid for the *Marble Island* cargo.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Subsequent appeals by both parties were dismissed.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Regarding the *Aegis Fame* shipping, the contract was frustrated and therefore Cubazukar were not in breach.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The commemoration of the coup is associated with competing narratives about its causes and effects.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The coup has been commemorated by detractors and supporters in various ways.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] On 11 September 1975, Pinochet lit the Llama de la Libertad (lit.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] 'Flame of Liberty') to commemorate the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Avenida Nueva Providencia in Providencia, Santiago, was renamed Avenida 11 de Septiembre in 1980.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] In the 30th anniversary of the coup President Ricardo Lagos inaugurated the Morandé 80 entrance to La Moneda.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] This entrance to the presidential palace had been erased during the repairs the dictatorship did to the building after the bombing.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The 40th anniversary of the coup in 2013 was particularly intense.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] That year the name of Avenida 11 de Septiembre was reversed to the original Avenida Nueva Providencia.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The Association of Chilean Magistrates issued a public statement in early September 2013 recognizing the past unwillingness of judges to protect those persecuted by dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] On 11 September 2013 hundreds of Chileans posed as dead in the streets of Santiago in remembrance of the ones "disappeared" by the dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The centre-left opposition refused to attend the commemoration event organized by Sebastián Piñera's right-wing government, organizing a separate event instead.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Osvaldo Andrade of the Socialist Party explained that attendance was not viable as Piñera's government was "packed with passive accomplices" of the dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Some right-wing politicians also declined the invitation.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Presidential candidate Michelle Bachelet planned to spend the day visiting Museum of Memory and Human Rights.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] President Piñera held an unusual speech in which he denounced "passive accomplices" like news reporters who deliberately changed or omitted the truth and judges who rejected recursos de amparos that could have saved lives.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] People who knew things or could have known things but decided to stay quiet were also criticized as passive accomplices in Piñera's speech.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Many new films, theatre plays, and photography expositions were held to cast light on the abuses and censorship of the dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The number of new books published on the subject in 2013 was such that it constituted an editorial boom.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The Museum of Memory and Human Rights also displayed a collection of declassified CIA, FBI, Defense Department, and White House records illustrating the U.S. role in the dictatorship and the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Conferences and seminars on the subject of coup were also held.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Various series and interviews with politicians about the coup and the dictatorship were aired on Chilean TV in 2013.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Ahead of the 50th anniversary of the coup in 2023, the United States, under the Biden administration, declassified President Nixon's daily briefs on Chile from 8 to 11 September 1973.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The document for 8 September read: "A number of reports have been received... indicating the possibility of an early military coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] The right-wing opposition called it "biased" and refused to sign it.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Others who attended were former Uruguayan president José Mujica and lead Rage Against the Machine guitarist Tom Morello, who said that the United States "shares responsibility" for the coup.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Surveys showed that 60% of Chileans surveyed were not interested in the commemoration, while another poll claimed that nearly 40% believed Pinochet "modernised" the country.
[src:allendism/1973-chilean-coup-d-état-p02] Other data found that more than a third of Chileans believed the coup was justified.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] General elections were held in Chile on 11 December 1993 to elect the President, members of the Chamber of Deputies and elected members of the Senate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle of the Concertación alliance was elected president, and the alliance also won a majority of seats in the Chamber of Deputies and maintained its majority in the Senate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] As of 2026, this is the most recent presidential election that did not result in a runoff.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] The Concertación, which had governed with Patricio Aylwin since 1990, needed to choose a successor who would run as their presidential candidate in the 1993 elections.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] To determine their candidate, the parties decided to hold primary elections, marking a historic milestone as it was the first time in Chile that a political coalition used this mechanism to select its sole candidate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Participation in these primaries required prior registration of voters, and there was no law or support from the Election Certification Tribunal (Tricel) or the Electoral Service (Servel) to regulate them.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] The Christian Democratic Party (PDC) chose Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle, the son of former President Eduardo Frei Montalva, as their candidate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Frei Ruiz-Tagle had previously run as a pre-candidate for the Concertación in the 1989 presidential election, but was unsuccessful.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] He then focused on strengthening his position within the PDC and achieved this by winning a senatorial election in the Santiago Oriente constituency in 1989 and becoming the party's president in 1990.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] The other pre-candidate was Ricardo Lagos Escobar, a prominent leader of the Party for Democracy (PPD), who also had the support of the Socialist Party (PS) due to his participation in the "No" campaign in the 1988 plebiscite.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Lagos had run as a senatorial candidate for the Santiago Poniente constituency in 1989, but despite finishing second, he lost due to the workings of the binomial electoral system.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] In 1990, he became Minister of Education in the Aylwin government, a position he held until 1992 when he left to begin his presidential campaign.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] An unsuccessful attempt was made to nominate Senator Anselmo Sule of the Radical Party (PR) and Cristián Reitze, president of the Humanist Green Alliance party, as candidates.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Reitze later left the Concertación after realizing that there was a move to exclude him from the primary.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] On May 23, 1993, the primaries were held, and Frei won by 64% of the vote, officially becoming the candidate on May 30.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] The PS and PPD respected the outcome and supported the chosen candidate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] In 1992, the largest right-wing party at the time, Renovación Nacional (RN), had two presidential pre-candidates: Senator for Santiago Oriente Sebastián Piñera and Deputy for Las Condes, Vitacura, and Lo Barnechea Evelyn Matthei.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] However, the aftermath of the *Piñeragate* political scandal that same year put an end to their aspirations, prompting RN to search for a new candidate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Manuel Feliú was ultimately selected as the replacement.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] The Independent Democratic Union (UDI) initially nominated Jovino Novoa, its president, as its pre-candidate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] However, there was a third candidate who gained support from various right-wing parties, particularly the UDI.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] This candidate was Arturo Alessandri Besa, an independent senator for Antofagasta who had family ties to two former presidents: Jorge Alessandri and Arturo Alessandri Palma.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] A convention was held on August 8, 1993, at the Diego Portales Building to choose the coalition's candidate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] The parties had been in conflict for several months over the mechanism for selecting the sole candidate, even considering primaries and who would run in them.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] José Piñera Echenique, the former Labor Minister in the government led by Augusto Pinochet and brother of Senator Piñera, withdrew from the convention because he believed that the bloc's candidate should be elected through primaries.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Additionally, Francisco Javier Errázuriz was considered as a potential candidate, supported by his party, the Union of Center-Center (UCC), the National Party (PN), and the Party of the South (SUR).
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] However, negotiations over parliamentary seats led him to abandon his decision.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] A total of 1,847 delegates from the coalition participated in the convention, including 547 from RN, 449 from UDI, 391 from the UCC, 46 from SUR, and 44 from the PN.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] As per the agreed terms, a second vote had to be held if no candidate obtained more than two-thirds of the total votes.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] However, after the results of the first vote were announced, Feliú withdrew his candidacy in favor of Alessandri.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Despite efforts, Alessandri's presidential campaign failed to attract voters.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] After the Humanist Green Alliance (AHV) withdrew from the Concertación, they launched the candidacy of Cristián Reitze, who based his campaign on the humanist principles of Silo, as well as the parliamentary work of the former AHV representative for La Reina and Peñalolén, Laura Rodríguez.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Marín emerged as the initial winner, but due to the close vote, a second round of deliberation was held, resulting in the selection of Pizarro as the MIDA candidate.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] His candidacy was officially registered with the Servel through the collection of signatures, as required for any independent candidacy under Law 18,700.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Pizarro's campaign was known for its aggressive and tough tone, representing the left wing that identified with the policies of the Salvador Allende-led Popular Unity government.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Manfred Max-Neef, an independent ecologist and economist, was also a candidate for the election with support from various social organizations, Mapuche communities, and sectors of the Christian Left, MAPU, and the Workers' Party.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] His campaign aimed to give voice to issues that were absent from public opinion, strengthen civil society, and create a scaled economy as an alternative to the alleged prevailing neoliberalism.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] He also positioned himself as completely horizontal on the political spectrum, which allowed him to attract votes from the Concertación, the right, the MIDA, and the AHV.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] José Piñera launched his candidacy in January, but when he realized that Unión por el Progreso de Chile closed its doors to him, he continued on his own path.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] He began as a representative of people who did not identify with the political class, but later represented sectors identified with Pinochet and the dictatorship.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] As a result, he received support from collaborators of that dictatorship, such as Mónica Madariaga and Sergio Melnick, among others.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] He managed to take a considerable number of votes away from Alessandri's candidacy.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Juan Antonio Torres Araya, a representative of the Retirees' Party, was considered as a potential candidate but his candidacy did not succeed because the Electoral Service (Servel) rejected over half of the signatures submitted to register his candidacy.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] He eventually threw his support behind Alessandri.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] The independent candidacy of Gonzalo Townsend Pinochet, the nephew of Augusto Pinochet, was successfully registered.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] Despite having run as a candidate for the Union of Center Center in the San Joaquín commune's municipal elections the previous year, Townsend aimed to represent the Acción Pinochetista Unitaria, a defender of the dictatorship's work, in the general election.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] However, after two weeks, Servel invalidated the candidacy as the candidacy had been sponsored by "more than 5% of people affiliated with political parties".
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] After his candidacy was rejected by the electoral agency, Gonzalo Townsend made a request that was ultimately denied.
[src:allendism/1993-chilean-general-election] He accused the process of being a ploy to prevent his participation as a candidate and finally called for casting a null vote in the presidential elections.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The **Age of Enlightenment**, also known as the **Age of Reason** or simply **the Enlightenment**, was a period of intellectual and cultural flourishing in Europe and Western civilization, emerging in the late 17th century in Western Europe.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It reached its peak in the 18th century as its ideas spread more widely across Europe and into the European colonies in the Americas and Oceania.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Characterized by an emphasis on reason, empirical evidence, and the scientific method, the Enlightenment promoted ideals of individual liberty, religious tolerance, progress, and natural rights.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Its thinkers advocated for constitutional government, the separation of church and state, and the application of rational principles to social and political reform.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment emerged from and built upon the Scientific Revolution of the 16th and 17th centuries, which had established new methods of empirical inquiry through the work of figures such as Galileo Galilei, Johannes Kepler, Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, Christiaan Huygens, and Isaac Newton.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Philosophical foundations were laid by thinkers including René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, and John Locke, whose ideas about reason, natural rights, and empirical knowledge became central to Enlightenment thought.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Others cite the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687) as the culmination of the Scientific Revolution and the beginning of the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European historians traditionally dated its beginning with the death of Louis XIV of France in 1715 and its end with the outbreak of the French Revolution in 1789.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many historians now date the end of the Enlightenment as the start of the 19th century, with the latest proposed year being the death of Immanuel Kant in 1804.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The movement was characterized by the widespread circulation of ideas through new institutions: scientific academies, literary salons, coffeehouses, Masonic lodges, and an expanding print culture of books, journals, and pamphlets.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The ideas of the Enlightenment undermined the authority of the monarchy and religious officials and paved the way for the political revolutions of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A variety of 19th-century movements, including liberalism, socialism, and neoclassicism, trace their intellectual heritage to the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] By contrast, other intellectual currents included arguments in favour of anti-Christianity, Deism and Atheism, accompanied by demands for secular states, bans on religious education, suppression of monasteries, the suppression of the Jesuits, and the expulsion of religious orders.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment also faced contemporary criticism, later termed the "Counter-Enlightenment" by Sir Isaiah Berlin, which defended traditional religious and political authorities against rationalist critique.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment was preceded by and closely associated with the Scientific Revolution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Earlier philosophers whose work influenced the Enlightenment included Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, Pierre Bayle, and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some of the figures of the Enlightenment included Cesare Beccaria, George Berkeley, Denis Diderot, David Hume, Immanuel Kant, Lord Monboddo, Montesquieu, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Adam Smith, Roger Williams, Hugo Grotius, and Voltaire.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] One of the most influential Enlightenment publications was the **Encyclopédie** (*Encyclopedia*).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Published between 1751 and 1772 in 35 volumes, it was compiled by Diderot, Jean le Rond d'Alembert, and a team of 150 others.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The *Encyclopédie* helped spread the ideas of the Enlightenment across Europe and beyond.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bacon's empiricism and Descartes' rationalist philosophy laid the foundation for enlightenment thinking.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' attempt to construct the sciences on a secure metaphysical foundation was not as successful as his method of doubt applied to philosophy, which led to a dualistic doctrine of mind and matter.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His skepticism was refined by Locke's *Essay Concerning Human Understanding* (1690) and Hume's writings in the 1740s.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' dualism was challenged by Spinoza's uncompromising assertion of the unity of matter in his *Tractatus* (1670) and *Ethics* (1677).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The moderate variety tended to be deistic whereas the radical tendency separated the basis of morality entirely from theology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both lines of thought were eventually opposed by a conservative Counter-Enlightenment which sought a return to faith.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the mid-18th century, Paris became the center of philosophic and scientific activity challenging traditional doctrines and dogmas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] After the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, the relationship between church and the absolutist government was very strong.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The early enlightenment emerged in protest to these circumstances, gaining ground under the support of Madame de Pompadour, the mistress of Louis XV.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Called the *Siècle des Lumières,* the philosophical movement of the Enlightenment had already started by the early 18th century, when Pierre Bayle launched the popular and scholarly Enlightenment critique of religion.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As a skeptic Bayle only partially accepted the philosophy and principles of rationality.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He did draw a strict boundary between morality and religion.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The political philosopher Montesquieu introduced the idea of a separation of powers in a government, a concept which was enthusiastically adopted by the authors of the United States Constitution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the *philosophes* of the French Enlightenment were not revolutionaries and many were members of the nobility, their ideas played an important part in undermining the legitimacy of the Old Regime and shaping the French Revolution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume became a major figure in the skeptical philosophical and empiricist traditions of philosophy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom and political authority, as well as map out a view of the public sphere through private and public reason.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant's work continued to influence German intellectual life and European philosophy more broadly well into the 20th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Mary Wollstonecraft was one of England's earliest feminist philosophers.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She argued for a society based on reason and that women as well as men should be treated as rational beings.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She is best known for her 1792 work, *A Vindication of the Rights of Woman*.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science played an important role in Enlightenment discourse and thought.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many Enlightenment writers and thinkers had backgrounds in the sciences and associated scientific advancement with the overthrow of religion and traditional authority in favour of the development of free speech and thought.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The experiments of Antoine Lavoisier were used to create the first modern chemical plants in Paris, and the experiments of the Montgolfier brothers enabled them to launch the first manned flight in a hot air balloon in 1783.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Broadly speaking, Enlightenment science greatly valued empiricism and rational thought and was embedded with the Enlightenment ideal of advancement and progress.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The study of science, under the heading of natural philosophy, was divided into physics and a conglomerate grouping of chemistry and natural history, which included anatomy, biology, geology, mineralogy, and zoology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As with most Enlightenment views, the benefits of science were not seen universally: Rousseau criticized the sciences for distancing man from nature and not operating to make people happier.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science during the Enlightenment was dominated by scientific societies and academies, which had largely replaced universities as centres of scientific research and development.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Societies and academies were also the backbone of the maturation of the scientific profession.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Scientific academies and societies grew out of the Scientific Revolution as the creators of scientific knowledge, in contrast to the scholasticism of the university.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some societies created or retained links to universities, but contemporary sources distinguished universities from scientific societies by claiming that the university's utility was in the transmission of knowledge while societies functioned to create knowledge.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As the role of universities in institutionalized science began to diminish, learned societies became the cornerstone of organized science.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Official scientific societies were chartered by the state to provide technical expertise.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Most societies were granted permission to oversee their own publications, control the election of new members and the administration of the society.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the 18th century, a very large number of official academies and societies were founded in Europe; by 1789 there were over 70 official scientific societies.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In reference to this growth, Bernard de Fontenelle coined the term "the Age of Academies" to describe the 18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Another important development was the popularization of science among an increasingly literate population.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] *Philosophes* introduced the public to many scientific theories, most notably through the *Encyclopédie* and the popularization of Newtonianism by Voltaire and Émilie du Châtelet.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some historians have marked the 18th century as a drab period in the history of science.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The century saw significant advancements in the practice of medicine, mathematics, and physics; the development of biological taxonomy; a new understanding of magnetism and electricity; and the maturation of chemistry as a discipline, which established the foundations of modern chemistry.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The influence of science began appearing more commonly in poetry and literature.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While some societies were established with ties to universities or maintained existing ones contemporary sources often distinguished between the two, asserting that universities primarily served to transmit knowledge, whereas scientific societies were oriented toward the creation of new knowledge.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] James Thomson penned his "A Poem to the Memory of Sir Isaac Newton," which mourned the loss of Newton and praised his science and legacy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Modern sociology largely originated from this movement, and Hume's philosophical concepts that directly influenced James Madison (and thus the U.S.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution), and as popularised by Dugald Stewart was the basis of classical liberalism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In 1776, Adam Smith published *The Wealth of Nations,* often considered the first work on modern economics as it had an immediate impact on British economic policy that continues into the 21st century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It was immediately preceded and influenced by Anne Robert Jacques Turgot's drafts of *Reflections on the Formation and Distribution of Wealth* (1766).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Smith acknowledged indebtedness and possibly was the original English translator.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Beccaria, a jurist, criminologist, philosopher, and politician and one of the great Enlightenment writers, became famous for his masterpiece *Dei delitti e delle pene* (Of Crimes and Punishments, 1764).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His treatise, translated into 22 languages, condemned torture and the death penalty and was a founding work in the field of penology and the classical school of criminology by promoting criminal justice.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Francesco Mario Pagano wrote studies such as *Saggi politici* (Political Essays, 1783); and *Considerazioni sul processo criminale* (Considerations on the Criminal Trial, 1787), which established him as an international authority on criminal law.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has long been seen as the foundation of modern Western political and intellectual culture.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment brought political modernization to the West, in terms of introducing democratic values and institutions and the creation of modern, liberal democracies.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This thesis has been widely accepted by scholars and has been reinforced by the large-scale studies by Robert Darnton, Roy Porter, and, most recently, by Jonathan Israel.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment thought was deeply influential in the political realm.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European rulers such as Catherine II of Russia, Joseph II of Austria, and Frederick II of Prussia tried to apply Enlightenment thought on religious and political tolerance, which became known as enlightened absolutism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution during its framing in 1787.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke, one of the most influential Enlightenment thinkers, based his governance philosophy on social contract theory, a subject that permeated Enlightenment political thought.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] English philosopher Thomas Hobbes ushered in this new debate with his work *Leviathan* in 1651.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Locke and Rousseau developed social contract theories in *Two Treatises of Government* and *Discourse on Inequality*, respectively.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While quite different works, Locke, Hobbes, and Rousseau agreed that a social contract, in which the government's authority lies in the consent of the governed, is necessary for man to live in civil society.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke defines the state of nature as a condition in which humans are rational and follow natural law, in which all men are born equal and with the right to life, liberty, and property.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] However, when one citizen breaks the law of nature both the transgressor and the victim enter into a state of war, from which it is virtually impossible to break free.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore, Locke said that individuals enter into civil society to protect their natural rights via an "unbiased judge" or common authority, such as courts.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In contrast, Rousseau's conception relies on the supposition that "civil man" is corrupted, while "natural man" has no want he cannot fulfill himself.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Natural man is only taken out of the state of nature when the inequality associated with private property is established.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rousseau said that people join into civil society via the social contract to achieve unity while preserving individual freedom.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This is embodied in the sovereignty of the general will, the moral and collective legislative body constituted by citizens.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke is known for his statement that individuals have a right to "Life, Liberty, and Property," and his belief that the natural right to property is derived from labor.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Declaration of Independence and the French National Constituent Assembly's Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some *philosophes* argued that the establishment of a contractual basis of rights would lead to the market mechanism and capitalism, the scientific method, religious tolerance, and the organization of states into self-governing republics through democratic means.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In this view, the tendency of the *philosophes* in particular to apply rationality to every problem is considered the essential change.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Although much of Enlightenment political thought was dominated by social contract theorists, Hume and Ferguson criticized this camp.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume's essay *Of the Original Contract* argues that governments derived from consent are rarely seen and civil government is grounded in a ruler's habitual authority and force.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It is precisely because of the ruler's authority over-and-against the subject that the subject tacitly consents, and Hume says that the subjects would "never imagine that their consent made him sovereign," rather the authority did so.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Similarly, Ferguson did not believe citizens built the state, rather polities grew out of social development.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In his 1767 *An Essay on the History of Civil Society,* Ferguson uses the four stages of progress, a theory that was popular in Scotland at the time, to explain how humans advance from a hunting and gathering society to a commercial and civil society without agreeing to a social contract.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Rousseau's and Locke's social contract theories rest on the presupposition of natural rights, which are not a result of law or custom but are things that all men have in pre-political societies and are therefore universal and inalienable.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The most famous natural right formulation comes from Locke's *Second Treatise,* when he introduces the state of nature.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, the law of nature is grounded on mutual security or the idea that one cannot infringe on another's natural rights, as every man is equal and has the same inalienable rights.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These natural rights include perfect equality and freedom, as well as the right to preserve life and property.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues against indentured servitude on the basis that enslaving oneself goes against the law of nature because a person cannot surrender their own rights: freedom is absolute, and no one can take it away.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues that one person cannot enslave another because it is morally reprehensible, although he introduces a caveat by saying that enslavement of a lawful captive in time of war would not go against one's natural rights.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The leaders of the Enlightenment were not especially democratic, as they more often look to absolute monarchs as the key to imposing reforms designed by the intellectuals.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In several nations, rulers welcomed leaders of the Enlightenment at court and asked them to help design laws and programs to reform the system, typically to build stronger states.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These rulers are called "enlightened despots" by historians.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They included Frederick the Great of Prussia, Catherine the Great of Russia, Leopold II of Tuscany and Joseph II of Austria.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Joseph was over-enthusiastic, announcing many reforms that had little support so that revolts broke out and his regime became a comedy of errors, and nearly all his programs were reversed.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Senior ministers Pombal in Portugal and Johann Friedrich Struensee in Denmark also governed according to Enlightenment ideals.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In Poland, the model constitution of 1791 expressed Enlightenment ideals, but was in effect for only one year before the nation was partitioned among its neighbors.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] More enduring were the cultural achievements, which created a nationalist spirit in Poland.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Frederick the Great, the king of Prussia from 1740 to 1786, saw himself as a leader of the Enlightenment and patronized philosophers and scientists at his court in Berlin.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Voltaire, who had been imprisoned and maltreated by the French government, was eager to accept Frederick's invitation to live at his palace.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has been frequently linked to the American Revolution of 1776 and the French Revolution of 1789—both had some intellectual influence from Thomas Jefferson.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A key aspect of this era was a profound shift from the absolute monarchies of Europe, which asserted the "divine right" to rule.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] John Locke rejected this view in his writings on the Two Treatises of Government (1689).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He asserted that citizens were seen to possess natural rights, including life, liberty, and property.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore governments exist to protect these rights through the "consent of the governed." The clash between these competing ethos often resulted in violent upheaval in differing ways.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In France, Ancien régime, with its rigid social hierarchy and absolute monarchical power, was systematically dismantled during the French Revolution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the American Revolution focused more on breaking free from a government - represented by King George III and Parliament - that colonists felt did not adequately represent their interests.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Alexis de Tocqueville proposed the French Revolution as the inevitable result of the radical opposition created in the 18th century between the monarchy and the men of letters of the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These men of letters constituted a sort of "substitute aristocracy that was both all-powerful and without real power." This illusory power came from the rise of "public opinion," born when absolutist centralization removed the nobility and the bourgeoisie from the political sphere.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "literary politics" that resulted promoted a discourse of equality and was hence in fundamental opposition to the monarchical regime.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment era religious commentary was a response to the preceding century of religious conflict in Europe, especially the Thirty Years' War.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Theologians of the Enlightenment wanted to reform their faith to its generally non-confrontational roots and to limit the capacity for religious controversy to spill over into politics and warfare while still maintaining a true faith in God.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For moderate Christians, this meant a return to simple Scripture.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke abandoned the corpus of theological commentary in favor of an "unprejudiced examination" of the Word of God alone.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He determined the essence of Christianity to be a belief in Christ the redeemer and recommended avoiding more detailed debate.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the *Jefferson Bible,* Thomas Jefferson went further and dropped any passages dealing with miracles, visitations of angels, and the resurrection of Jesus after his death, as he tried to extract the practical Christian moral code of the New Testament.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment scholars sought to curtail the political power of organized religion and thereby prevent another age of intolerant religious war.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Spinoza determined to remove politics from contemporary and historical theology (e.g., disregarding Judaic law).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Moses Mendelssohn advised affording no political weight to any organized religion but instead recommended that each person follow what they found most convincing.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They believed a good religion based in instinctive morals and a belief in God should not theoretically need force to maintain order in its believers, and both Mendelssohn and Spinoza judged religion on its moral fruits, not the logic of its theology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Several novel ideas about religion developed with the Enlightenment, including deism and talk of atheism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to Thomas Paine, deism is the simple belief in God the Creator with no reference to the Bible or any other miraculous source.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Instead, the deist relies solely on personal reason to guide his creed, which was eminently agreeable to many thinkers of the time.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Atheism was much discussed, but there were few proponents.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Wilson and Reill note: "In fact, very few enlightened intellectuals, even when they were vocal critics of Christianity, were true atheists.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rather, they were critics of orthodox belief, wedded rather to skepticism, deism, vitalism, or perhaps pantheism." Some followed Pierre Bayle and argued that atheists could indeed be moral men.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many others like Voltaire held that without belief in a God who punishes evil, the moral order of society was undermined; that is, since atheists gave themselves to no supreme authority and no law and had no fear of eternal consequences, they were far more likely to disrupt society.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bayle observed that, in his day, "prudent persons will always maintain an appearance of [religion]," and he believed that even atheists could hold concepts of honor and go beyond their own self-interest to create and interact in society.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke said that if there were no God and no divine law, the result would be moral anarchy: every individual "could have no law but his own will, no end but himself.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "Radical Enlightenment" promoted the concept of separating church and state, an idea that is often credited to Locke.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to his principle of the social contract, Locke said that the government lacked authority in the realm of individual conscience, as this was something rational people could not cede to the government for it or others to control.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, this created a natural right in the liberty of conscience, which he said must therefore remain protected from any government authority.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These views on religious tolerance and the importance of individual conscience, along with the social contract, became particularly influential in the American colonies and the drafting of the United States Constitution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association in Connecticut, Thomas Jefferson calls for a "wall of separation between church and state" at the federal level.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He previously had supported successful efforts to disestablish the Church of England in Virginia and authored the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Jefferson's political ideals were greatly influenced by the writings of Locke, Bacon, and Newton, whom he considered the three greatest men that ever lived.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment took hold in most European countries and influenced nations globally, often with a specific local emphasis.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] For example, in France it became associated with anti-government and anti-Church radicalism, while in Germany it reached deep into the middle classes, where it expressed a spiritualistic and nationalistic tone without threatening governments or established churches.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, the government was hostile, and the *philosophes* fought against its censorship, sometimes being imprisoned or hounded into exile.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The British government, for the most part, ignored the Enlightenment's leaders in England and Scotland, although it did give Newton a knighthood and a very lucrative government office.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A common theme among most countries which derived Enlightenment ideas from Europe was the intentional non-inclusion of Enlightenment philosophies pertaining to slavery.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1791, the Haitian Revolution, a slave rebellion by emancipated slaves against French colonial rule in the colony of Saint-Domingue, broke out.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The very existence of an English Enlightenment has been hotly debated by scholars.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The majority of textbooks on British history make little or no mention of an English Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Some surveys of the entire Enlightenment include England and others ignore it, although they do include coverage of such major intellectuals as Joseph Addison, Edward Gibbon, John Locke, Isaac Newton, Alexander Pope, Joshua Reynolds, and Jonathan Swift.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freethinking, a term describing those who stood in opposition to the institution of the Church, and the literal belief in the Bible, can be said to have begun in England no later than 1713, when Anthony Collins wrote his "Discourse of Free-thinking," which gained substantial popularity.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This essay attacked the clergy of all churches and was a plea for deism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Roy Porter argues that the reasons for this neglect were the assumptions that the movement was primarily French-inspired, that it was largely a-religious or anti-clerical, and that it stood in outspoken defiance to the established order.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter admits that after the 1720s England could claim thinkers to equal Diderot, Voltaire, or Rousseau.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, its leading intellectuals such as Gibbon, Edmund Burke and Samuel Johnson were all quite conservative and supportive of the standing order.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter says the reason was that Enlightenment had come early to England and had succeeded such that the culture had accepted political liberalism, philosophical empiricism, and religious toleration, positions which intellectuals on the continent had to fight against powerful odds.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Furthermore, England rejected the collectivism of the continent and emphasized the improvement of individuals as the main goal of enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Derek Hirst, the 1640s and 1650s saw a revived economy characterised by growth in manufacturing, the elaboration of financial and credit instruments, and the commercialisation of communication.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The gentry found time for leisure activities, such as horse racing and bowling.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the high culture important innovations included the development of a mass market for music, increased scientific research, and an expansion of publishing.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] All the trends were discussed in depth at the newly established coffee houses.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the Scottish Enlightenment, the principles of sociability, equality, and utility were disseminated in schools and universities, many of which used sophisticated teaching methods which blended philosophy with daily life.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scotland's major cities created an intellectual infrastructure of mutually supporting institutions such as schools, universities, reading societies, libraries, periodicals, museums, and Masonic lodges.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Several Americans, especially Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Jefferson, played a major role in bringing Enlightenment ideas to the New World and in influencing British and French thinkers.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin was influential for his political activism and for his advances in physics.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin also broadly encouraged the individual's rights and responsibilities to serve as an educated and informed citizen.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He published yearly the widely popular, *Poor Richard's Almanack,* filled with witty quotes encouraging disciplined self-learning, such as "Early to bed, early to rise, makes a man healthy, wealthy and wise." The cultural exchange during the Enlightenment ran in both directions across the Atlantic.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Thinkers such as Paine, Locke, and Rousseau all take Native American cultural practices as examples of natural freedom.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Americans closely followed English and Scottish political ideas, as well as some French thinkers such as Montesquieu.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] As deists, they were influenced by ideas of John Toland and Matthew Tindal.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was a great emphasis upon liberty, republicanism, and religious tolerance.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was no respect for monarchy or inherited political power.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Deists reconciled science and religion by rejecting prophecies, miracles, and biblical theology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leading deists included Thomas Paine in *The Age of Reason* and Thomas Jefferson in his short *Jefferson Bible,* from which he removed all supernatural aspects.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Jewish Enlightenment, or *Haskalah* (Hebrew: הַשְׂכָּלָה, "education") was an intellectual movement among the Jews of Central and Eastern Europe, with a certain influence on those in Western Europe and the Muslim world.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It arose as a defined ideological worldview during the 1770s, and its last stage ended around 1881, with the rise of Jewish nationalism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement advocated against Jewish reclusiveness, encouraged the adoption of prevalent attire over traditional dress, while also working to diminish the authority of traditional community institutions such as rabbinic courts and boards of elders.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Early Dutch Enlightenment (1640–1720), many books were translated from Latin, French or English to Dutch, often at the risk of their translators and publishers.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the 1720s, the Dutch Republic had also become a major center for printing and exporting banned books to France.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Implanted in Netherlandish culture, vernacular rationalism brought the Dutch to take advantage of the intellectual philosophy the enlightenment spread.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The most famous figure of the Dutch Enlightenment was Baruch Spinoza.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The French Enlightenment was influenced by England and in turn influenced other national enlightenments.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Prussia took the lead among the German states in sponsoring the political reforms that Enlightenment thinkers urged absolute rulers to adopt.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There were important movements as well in the smaller states of Bavaria, Saxony, Hanover, and the Palatinate.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In each case, Enlightenment values became accepted and led to significant political and administrative reforms that laid the groundwork for the creation of modern states.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The princes of Saxony, for example, carried out an impressive series of fundamental fiscal, administrative, judicial, educational, cultural, and general economic reforms.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reforms were aided by the country's strong urban structure and influential commercial groups and modernized pre-1789 Saxony along the lines of classic Enlightenment principles.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Before 1750, the German upper classes looked to France for intellectual, cultural, and architectural leadership, as French was the language of high society.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the mid-18th century, the *Aufklärung* (The Enlightenment) had transformed German high culture in music, philosophy, science, and literature.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Christian Wolff was the pioneer as a writer who expounded the Enlightenment to German readers and legitimized German as a philosophic language.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Johann Gottfried von Herder broke new ground in philosophy and poetry, as a leader of the Sturm und Drang movement of proto-Romanticism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Weimar Classicism (*Weimarer Klassik*) was a cultural and literary movement based in Weimar that sought to establish a new humanism by synthesizing Romantic, classical, and Enlightenment ideas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement (from 1772 until 1805) involved Herder as well as polymath Johann Wolfgang von Goethe and Friedrich Schiller, a poet and historian.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The theatre principal Abel Seyler greatly influenced the development of German theatre and promoted serious German opera, new works and experimental productions, and the concept of a national theatre.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Herder argued that every group of people had its own particular identity, which was expressed in its language and culture.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This legitimized the promotion of German language and culture and helped shape the development of German nationalism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Schiller's plays expressed the restless spirit of his generation, depicting the hero's struggle against social pressures and the force of destiny.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German music, sponsored by the upper classes, came of age under composers Johann Sebastian Bach, Joseph Haydn, and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In remote Königsberg, Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom, and political authority.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Kant's work contained basic tensions that would continue to shape German thought—and indeed all of European philosophy—well into the 20th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German Enlightenment won the support of princes, aristocrats, and the middle classes, and it permanently reshaped the culture.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, there was a conservatism among the elites that warned against going too far.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1788, Prussia issued an "Edict on Religion" that forbade preaching any sermon that undermined popular belief in the Holy Trinity or the Bible.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The goal was to avoid theological disputes that might impinge on domestic tranquility.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Men who doubted the value of Enlightenment favoured the measure, but so too did many supporters.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German universities had created a closed elite that could debate controversial issues among themselves, but spreading them to the public was seen as too risky.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This intellectual elite was favoured by the state, but that might be reversed if the process of the Enlightenment proved politically or socially destabilizing.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, Austria was under Habsburg rule.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reign of Maria Theresa, the first Habsburg monarch to be considered influenced by the Enlightenment in some areas, was marked by a mix of enlightenment and conservatism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Her son Joseph II's brief reign was marked by this conflict, with his ideology of Josephinism facing opposition.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph II carried out numerous reforms in the spirit of the Enlightenment, which affected, for example, the school system, monasteries and the legal system.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Emperor Leopold II, who was an early opponent of capital punishment, had a brief and contentious rule that was mostly marked by relations with France.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Similarly, Emperor Francis II's rule was primarily marked by relations with France.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment also appeared in literature and theater works.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph von Sonnenfels was an important representative.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In music, Austrian musicians such as Joseph Haydn and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart were associated with the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Modern Greek Enlightenment (Greek: Διαφωτισμός, Diafotismós) was the Greek expression of the Enlightenment, characterized by an intellectual and philosophical movement within the Greek community.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At this time, many Greeks were dispersed across the Ottoman Empire, with some residing on the Ionian Islands, in Venice, and other parts of Italy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century, while Hungary was part of the Habsburg Empire.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment is usually said to have begun in 1772 and was greatly influenced by French Enlightenment (through Vienna).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Romanian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century across the three major historical regions inhabited by Romanians: Transylvania, Wallachia, and Moldavia.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At that time, Transylvania was in the Habsburg Empire while Wallachia and Moldavia were vassals of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Transylvanian Enlightenment was represented by the Transylvanian School, a group of thinkers who promoted a cultural revival and rights for Romanians (who were marginalized by the Habsburgs).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Wallachian Enlightenment was represented by such figures as Dinicu Golescu (1777–1830), while the Moldavian Englightenment was headed by prince Dimitrie Cantemir (1673-1723).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment arrived relatively late in Switzerland, spreading from England, the Netherlands, and France toward the end of the 17th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement initially took hold in Protestant regions, where it gradually replaced orthodox religious thinking.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The 1712 victory of the reformed cantons of Zurich and Bern over the five Catholic cantons of central Switzerland in the Second War of Villmergen marked both a Protestant triumph and a victory for Enlightenment ideas in the economically more developed regions.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Switzerland, which lacked a central court or academy, the Enlightenment spread through the intellectual elite of reformed cities, particularly pastors educated in academies and colleges with strong humanist traditions.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss Enlightenment thinkers made significant contributions across multiple fields.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, Johann Jakob Bodmer and Johann Jakob Breitinger made Zurich a center of German literary innovation, while Albert von Haller's poetry represented the peak of Swiss Enlightenment literature.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean-Jacques Rousseau, considering himself both a Genevan and Swiss citizen, developed democratic republican theories that extended Genevan models to broader European federalist principles.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement was characterized by what scholars term "Helvetism" – specifically Swiss aspects including a Christian conception of natural law, patriotic ethics, and philosophical approaches grounded in practical pedagogy and economics.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most distinctively, Swiss Enlightenment thought celebrated Alpine nature, viewing Switzerland as the "land of shepherds" whose republican and federalist traditions were shaped by its mountain environment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement organized through numerous societies and publications, including the *Encyclopédie d'Yverdon* (1770-1780), which offered a moderate alternative to the French *Encyclopédie*.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss intellectuals gained international prominence, with many serving in foreign academies, particularly in Berlin under Frederick II and in St.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Italy, the main centers of diffusion of the Enlightenment were Naples and Milan: in both cities the intellectuals took public office and collaborated with the Bourbon and Habsburg administrations.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Naples, Antonio Genovesi, Ferdinando Galiani, and Gaetano Filangieri were active under the tolerant King Charles of Bourbon.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, the Neapolitan Enlightenment, like Vico's philosophy, remained almost always in the theoretical field.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Only later, many Enlighteners animated the unfortunate experience of the Parthenopean Republic.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Milan, however, the movement strove to find concrete solutions to problems.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The center of discussions was the magazine *Il Caffè* (1762–1766), founded by brothers Pietro and Alessandro Verri (famous philosophers and writers, as well as their brother Giovanni), who also gave life to the Accademia dei Pugni, founded in 1761.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Minor centers were Tuscany, Veneto, and Piedmont, where among others, Pompeo Neri worked.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Naples, Genovesi influenced a generation of southern Italian intellectuals and university students.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His textbook *Della diceosina, o sia della Filosofia del Giusto e dell'Onesto* (1766) was a controversial attempt to mediate between the history of moral philosophy on the one hand and the specific problems encountered by 18th-century commercial society on the other.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It contained the greater part of Genovesi's political, philosophical, and economic thought, which became a guidebook for Neapolitan economic and social development.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Science flourished as Alessandro Volta and Luigi Galvani made break-through discoveries in electricity.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Pietro Verri was a leading economist in Lombardy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Historian Joseph Schumpeter states he was "the most important pre-Smithian authority on Cheapness-and-Plenty." The most influential scholar on the Italian Enlightenment has been Franco Venturi.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Italy also produced some of the Enlightenment's greatest legal theorists, including Cesare Beccaria, Giambattista Vico, and Francesco Mario Pagano.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Charles II, the last Spanish Habsburg monarch, died his successor was from the French House of Bourbon, initiating a period of French Enlightenment influence in Spain and the Spanish Empire.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 18th Century, the Spanish continued to expand their empire in the Americas with the Spanish missions in California and established missions deeper inland in South America.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Under Charles III, the crown began to implement serious structural changes.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The monarchy curtailed the power of the Catholic Church, and established a standing military in Spanish America.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freer trade was promoted under *comercio libre* in which regions could trade with companies sailing from any other Spanish port, rather than the restrictive mercantile system.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The crown sent out scientific expeditions to assert Spanish sovereignty over territories it claimed but did not control, but also importantly to discover the economic potential of its far-flung empire.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Botanical expeditions sought plants that could be of use to the empire.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Charles IV gave Prussian scientist Alexander von Humboldt free rein to travel in Spanish America, usually closed to foreigners, and more importantly, access to crown officials to aid the success of his scientific expedition.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Napoleon invaded Spain in 1808, Ferdinand VII abdicated and Napoleon placed his brother Joseph Bonaparte on the throne.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] To add legitimacy to this move, the Bayonne Constitution was promulgated, which included representation from Spain's overseas components, but most Spaniards rejected the whole Napoleonic project.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Cortes de Cádiz (parliament) was convened to rule Spain in the absence of the legitimate monarch, Ferdinand.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The constitution was in effect from 1812 until 1814, when Napoleon was defeated and Ferdinand was restored to the throne of Spain.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Upon his return, Ferdinand repudiated the constitution and reestablished absolutist rule.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Haitian Revolution began in 1791 and ended in 1804 and shows how Enlightenment ideas "were part of complex transcultural flows." Radical ideas in Paris during and after the French Revolution were mobilized in Haiti, such as by Toussaint Louverture.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Portuguese Enlightenment was heavily marked by the rule of Prime Minister Marquis of Pombal under King Joseph I from 1756 to 1777.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His urbanistic ideas, also being the first large-scale example of earthquake engineering, became collectively known as Pombaline style, and were implemented throughout the kingdom during his stay in office.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His governance was as enlightened as ruthless, see for example the Távora affair.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, the first Enlightenment ideas in Portugal can be traced back to the diplomat, philosopher, and writer António Vieira who spent a considerable amount of his life in colonial Brazil denouncing discriminations against New Christians and the indigenous peoples in Brazil.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, enlightened literary movements such as the Arcádia Lusitana (lasting from 1756 until 1776, then replaced by the Nova Arcádia in 1790 until 1794) surfaced in the academic medium, in particular involving former students of the University of Coimbra.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A distinct member of this group was the poet Manuel Maria Barbosa du Bocage.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The physician António Nunes Ribeiro Sanches was also an important Enlightenment figure, contributing to the *Encyclopédie* and being part of the Russian court.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment influenced various economists and anti-colonial intellectuals throughout the Portuguese Empire, such as José de Azeredo Coutinho, José da Silva Lisboa, Cláudio Manoel da Costa, and Tomás Antônio Gonzaga.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Napoleonic invasion of Portugal had consequences for the Portuguese monarchy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] With the aid of the British navy, the Portuguese royal family was evacuated to Brazil, its most important colony.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Even though Napoleon had been defeated, the royal court remained in Brazil.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Liberal Revolution of 1820 forced the return of the royal family to Portugal.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The terms by which the restored king was to rule was a constitutional monarchy under the Constitution of Portugal.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Brazil declared its independence from Portugal in 1822 and became a monarchy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The existence of a Swedish Enlightenment has been debated by scholars.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Between 1718 and 1772, the Swedish Enlightenment overlapped with the period of parliamentary rule known in Swedish history as the Age of Liberty.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Russia, the government began to actively encourage the proliferation of arts and sciences in the mid-18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This era produced the first Russian university, library, theatre, public museum, and independent press.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Like other enlightened despots, Catherine the Great played a key role in fostering the arts, sciences and education.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] She used her own interpretation of Enlightenment ideals, assisted by notable international experts such as Voltaire (by correspondence) and in residence world class scientists such as Leonhard Euler and Peter Simon Pallas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The national Enlightenment differed from its Western European counterpart in that it promoted further modernization of all aspects of Russian life and was concerned with attacking the institution of serfdom in Russia.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Russian Enlightenment centered on the individual instead of societal enlightenment and encouraged the living of an enlightened life.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A powerful element was *prosveshchenie* which combined religious piety, erudition, and commitment to the spread of learning.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, it lacked the skeptical and critical spirit of the Western European Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment ideas (*oświecenie*) emerged late in Poland, as the Polish middle class was weaker and szlachta (nobility) culture (Sarmatism) together with the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth political system (Golden Liberty) were in deep crisis.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The political system was built on aristocratic republicanism, but was unable to defend itself against powerful neighbors Russia, Prussia, and Austria as they repeatedly sliced off regions until nothing was left of independent Poland.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Polish Enlightenment began in the 1730s–40s and especially in theatre and the arts peaked in the reign of King Stanisław August Poniatowski (second half of the 18th century).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Warsaw was a main centre after 1750, with an expansion of schools and educational institutions and the arts patronage held at the Royal Castle.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leaders promoted tolerance and more education.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] They included King Stanislaw II August and reformers Piotr Switkowski, Antoni Poplawski, Josef Niemcewicz, and Jósef Pawlinkowski, as well as Baudouin de Cortenay, a Polonized dramatist.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Opponents included Florian Jaroszewicz, Gracjan Piotrowski, Karol Wyrwicz, and Wojciech Skarszewski.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement went into decline with the Third Partition of Poland (1795) – a national tragedy inspiring a short period of sentimental writing – and ended in 1822, replaced by Romanticism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From 1641 to 1853, the Tokugawa shogunate of Japan enforced a policy called *kaikin.* The policy prohibited foreign contact with most outside countries.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During this time, Korea "aimed at isolation" and was known as the "hermit kingdom" but became awakened to Enlightenment ideas by the 1890s such as with the activities of the Independence Club.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Korea was influenced by China and Japan but also found its own Enlightenment path with the Korean intellectual Yu Kilchun who popularized the term Enlightenment throughout Korea.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 18th-century India, Tipu Sultan was an enlightened monarch, who "was one of the founding members of the (French) Jacobin Club in Seringapatam, had planted a liberty tree, and asked to be addressed as 'Tipu Citoyen,'" which means Citizen Tipu.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In parts of India, an important movement called the "Bengal Renaissance" led to Enlightenment reforms beginning in the 1820s.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment began to influence the Ottoman Empire in the 1830s and continued into the late 19th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Tanzimat was a period of reform in the Ottoman Empire that began with the Gülhane Hatt-ı Şerif in 1839 and ended with the First Constitutional Era in 1876.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Arab Enlightenment, or *Nahda* (Arabic: النّهضة, "the awakening"), was a cultural movement in Arab-populated regions of the Ottoman Empire such as Egypt, Lebanon, Syria, and Tunisia, during the second half of the 19th century and the early 20th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The *Nahda* is often traced to the cultural shock of the French invasion of Egypt and Syria in 1798, and the reformist drive of subsequent rulers such as Muhammad Ali of Egypt.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The idea of the Enlightenment has always been contested territory.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Keith Thomas, its supporters "hail it as the source of everything that is progressive about the modern world.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From the start, conservative and clerical defenders of traditional religion attacked materialism and skepticism as evil forces that encouraged immorality.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By 1794, they pointed to the Reign of Terror during the French Revolution as confirmation of their predictions.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Romantic philosophers argued that the Enlightenment's excessive dependence on reason was a mistake that it perpetuated, disregarding the bonds of history, myth, faith, and tradition that were necessary to hold society together.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Ritchie Robertson portrays it as a grand intellectual and political program, offering a "science" of society modeled on the powerful physical laws of Newton.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] "Social science" was seen as the instrument of human improvement.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It would expose truth and expand human happiness.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The rights of women and non-White people were generally overlooked in Enlightenment philosophy, which is often explicitly Eurocentric.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scientific racism first emerged at this time, bringing together traditional racism and new research methods.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Enlightenment, concepts of monogenism and polygenism became popular, though they would only be systematized epistemologically during the 19th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Monogenism contends that all races have a single origin, while polygenism is the idea that each race has a separate origin.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Until the 18th century, the words "race" and "species" were interchangeable.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The classification of non-European peoples as sub-human and irrational served to justify European dominance.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The term "Enlightenment" emerged in English in the latter part of the 19th century, with particular reference to French philosophy, as the equivalent of the French term *Lumières* (used first by Jean-Baptiste Dubos in 1733 and already well established by 1751).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Kant's 1784 essay "Beantwortung der Frage: Was ist Aufklärung?" ("Answering the Question: What is Enlightenment?"), the German term became *Aufklärung* (*aufklären* = to illuminate; *sich aufklären* = to clear up).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, scholars have never agreed on a definition of the Enlightenment or on its chronological or geographical extent.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Terms like *les Lumières* (French), *illuminism*o (Italian), *ilustración* (Spanish) and *Aufklärung* (German) referred to partly overlapping movements.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment historiography began in the period itself, from what Enlightenment figures said about their work.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A dominant element was the intellectual angle they took.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean le Rond d'Alembert's *Preliminary Discourse* of *l'Encyclopédie* provides a history of the Enlightenment which comprises a chronological list of developments in the realm of knowledge—of which the *Encyclopédie* forms the pinnacle.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1783, Mendelssohn referred to Enlightenment as a process by which man was educated in the use of reason.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Bertrand Russell saw the Enlightenment as a phase in a progressive development which began in antiquity and that reason and challenges to the established order were constant ideals throughout that time.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Although many of these philosophical ideals were picked up by Catholics, Russell argues that by the 18th century the Enlightenment was the principal manifestation of the schism that began with Martin Luther.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jonathan Israel rejects the attempts of postmodern and Marxian historians to understand the revolutionary ideas of the period purely as by-products of social and economic transformations.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He instead focuses on the history of ideas in the period from 1650 to the end of the 18th century and claims that it was the ideas themselves that caused the change that eventually led to the revolutions of the latter half of the 18th century and the early 19th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There is little consensus on the beginning of the Enlightenment, though several historians and philosophers argue that it was marked by Descartes' 1637 philosophy of *Cogito, ergo sum* ("I think, therefore I am"), which shifted the epistemological basis from external authority to internal certainty.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, many cited the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687), which built upon the work of earlier scientists and formulated the laws of motion and universal gravitation.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] French historians usually place the *Siècle des Lumières* ("Century of Enlightenments") between 1715 and 1789: from the beginning of the reign of Louis XV until the French Revolution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most scholars use the last years of the century, often choosing the French Revolution or the beginning of the Napoleonic Wars (1804) as a convenient point in time with which to date the end of the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In their 1947 book *Dialectic of Enlightenment,* Frankfurt School philosophers Max Horkheimer and Theodor W.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Extending Horkheimer and Adorno's argument, intellectual historian Jason Josephson Storm argues that any idea of the Enlightenment as a clearly defined period that is separate from the earlier Renaissance and later Romanticism or Counter-Enlightenment constitutes a myth.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Storm defends his categorization of the Enlightenment as "myth" by noting the regulative role ideas of a period of Enlightenment and disenchantment play in modern Western culture, such that belief in magic, spiritualism, and even religion appears somewhat taboo in intellectual strata.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 1970s, study of the Enlightenment expanded to include the ways Enlightenment ideas spread to European colonies and how they interacted with indigenous cultures and how the Enlightenment took place in formerly unstudied areas such as Italy, Greece, the Balkans, Poland, Hungary, and Russia.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Intellectuals such as Robert Darnton and Jürgen Habermas have focused on the social conditions of the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas described the creation of the "bourgeois public sphere" in 18th-century Europe, containing the new venues and modes of communication allowing for rational exchange.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas said that the public sphere was bourgeois, egalitarian, rational, and independent from the state, making it the ideal venue for intellectuals to critically examine contemporary politics and society, away from the interference of established authority.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] While the public sphere is generally an integral component of the social study of the Enlightenment, other historians have questioned whether the public sphere had these characteristics.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This approach studies the process of changing sociabilities and cultural practices during the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Elements of the public sphere included that it was egalitarian, that it discussed the domain of "common concern," and that argument was founded on reason.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Habermas uses the term "common concern" to describe those areas of political/social knowledge and discussion that were previously the exclusive territory of the state and religious authorities, now open to critical examination by the public sphere.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The values of this bourgeois public sphere included holding reason to be supreme, considering everything to be open to criticism (the public sphere is critical), and the opposition of secrecy of all sorts.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The creation of the public sphere has been associated with two long-term historical trends: the rise of the modern nation state and the rise of capitalism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The modern nation state in its consolidation of public power created by counterpoint a private realm of society independent of the state, which allowed for the public sphere.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Capitalism also increased society's autonomy and self-awareness, as well as an increasing need for the exchange of information.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the nascent public sphere expanded, it embraced a large variety of institutions, and the most commonly cited were coffee houses and cafés, salons and the literary public sphere, figuratively localized in the Republic of Letters.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the creation of the public sphere was helped by the aristocracy's move from the king's palace at Versailles to Paris in about 1720, since their rich spending stimulated the trade in luxuries and artistic creations, especially fine paintings.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The word "public" implies the highest level of inclusivity—the public sphere by definition should be open to all.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, this sphere was only public to relative degrees.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Cross-class influences occurred through noble and lower class participation in areas such as the coffeehouses and the Masonic lodges.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Because of the focus on reason over superstition, the Enlightenment cultivated the arts.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Emphasis on learning, art, and music became more widespread, especially with the growing middle class.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Areas of study such as literature, philosophy, science, and the fine arts increasingly explored subject matter to which the general public, in addition to the previously more segregated professionals and patrons, could relate.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As musicians depended more on public support, public concerts became increasingly popular and helped supplement performers' and composers' incomes.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The concerts also helped them to reach a wider audience.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Handel, for example, epitomized this with his highly public musical activities in London.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] He gained considerable fame there with performances of his operas and oratorios.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The music of Haydn and Mozart, with their Viennese Classical styles, are usually regarded as being the most in line with the Enlightenment ideals.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The desire to explore, record, and systematize knowledge had a meaningful impact on music publications.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rousseau's *Dictionnaire de musique* (published 1767 in Geneva and 1768 in Paris) was a leading text in the late 18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This widely available dictionary gave short definitions of words like genius and taste and was clearly influenced by the Enlightenment movement.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Another text influenced by Enlightenment values was Charles Burney's *A General History of Music: From the Earliest Ages to the Present Period* (1776), which was a historical survey and an attempt to rationalize elements in music systematically over time.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Recently, musicologists have shown renewed interest in the ideas and consequences of the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the economy and the middle class expanded, there was an increasing number of amateur musicians.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One manifestation of this involved women, who became more involved with music on a social level.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Women were already engaged in professional roles as singers and increased their presence in the amateur performers' scene, especially with keyboard music.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music publishers began to print music that amateurs could understand and play.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The majority of the works that were published were for keyboard, voice and keyboard, and chamber ensemble.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After these initial genres were popularized, from the mid-century on, amateur groups sang choral music, which then became a new trend for publishers to capitalize on.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increasing study of the fine arts, as well as access to amateur-friendly published works, led to more people becoming interested in reading and discussing music.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music magazines, reviews, and critical works which suited amateurs as well as connoisseurs began to surface.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *philosophes* spent a great deal of energy disseminating their ideas among educated men and women in cosmopolitan cities.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They used many venues, some of them quite new.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Republic of Letters was the sum of a number of Enlightenment ideals: an egalitarian realm governed by knowledge that could act across political boundaries and rival state power.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was a forum that supported "free public examination of questions regarding religion or legislation." Kant considered written communication essential to his conception of the public sphere; once everyone was a part of the "reading public," then society could be said to be enlightened.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The people who participated in the Republic of Letters, such as Diderot and Voltaire, are frequently known today as important Enlightenment figures.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While women were marginalized in the public culture of the Old Regime, the French Revolution destroyed the old cultural and economic restraints of patronage and corporatism (medieval guilds), opening French society to female participation, particularly in the literary sphere.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the established men of letters (*gens de lettres*) had fused with the elites (*les grands*) of French society by the mid-18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was Grub Street literature that was most read by the public during the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] According to Darnton, more importantly the Grub Street hacks inherited the "revolutionary spirit" once displayed by the *philosophes* and paved the way for the French Revolution by desacralizing figures of political, moral, and religious authority in France.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increased consumption of reading materials of all sorts was one of the key features of the "social" Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, demand for reading material extended outside of the realm of the commercial and outside the realm of the upper and middle classes, as evidenced by the bibliothèque bleue.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Literacy rates are difficult to gauge, but in France the rates doubled over the course of the 18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reflecting the decreasing influence of religion, the number of books about science and art published in Paris doubled from 1720 to 1780, while the number of books about religion dropped to just one-tenth of the total.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reading underwent serious changes in the 18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In particular, Rolf Engelsing has argued for the existence of a *reading revolution.* Until 1750, reading was done intensively: people tended to own a small number of books and read them repeatedly, often to small audience.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After 1750, people began to read "extensively," finding as many books as they could, increasingly reading them alone.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is supported by increasing literacy rates, particularly among women.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The vast majority of the reading public could not afford to own a private library, and while most of the state-run "universal libraries" set up in the 17th and 18th centuries were open to the public, they were not the only sources of reading material.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On one end of the spectrum was the *bibliothèque bleue,* a collection of cheaply produced books published in Troyes, France.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Intended for a largely rural and semi-literate audience these books included almanacs, retellings of medieval romances and condensed versions of popular novels, among other things.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While some historians have argued against the Enlightenment's penetration into the lower classes, the *bibliothèque bleue* represents at least a desire to participate in Enlightenment sociability.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Moving up the classes, a variety of institutions offered readers access to material without needing to buy anything.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Libraries that lent out their material for a small price started to appear, and occasionally bookstores would offer a small lending library to their patrons.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffee houses commonly offered books, journals, and sometimes even popular novels to their customers.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Tatler* and *The Spectator,* two influential periodicals sold from 1709 to 1714, were closely associated with coffee house culture in London, being both read and produced in various establishments in the city.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is an example of the triple or even quadruple function of the coffee house: reading material was often obtained, read, discussed, and even produced on the premises.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It is difficult to determine what people actually read during the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, examining the catalogs of private libraries gives an image skewed in favor of the classes wealthy enough to afford libraries and also ignores censored works unlikely to be publicly acknowledged.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For this reason, a study of publishing would be much more fruitful for discerning reading habits.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Across continental Europe, but in France especially, booksellers and publishers had to negotiate censorship laws of varying strictness.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie* narrowly escaped seizure and had to be saved by Malesherbes, the man in charge of the French censor.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, many publishing companies were conveniently located outside France so as to avoid overzealous French censors.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They would smuggle their merchandise across the border, where it would then be transported to clandestine booksellers or small-time peddlers.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The records of clandestine booksellers may give a better representation of what literate Frenchmen might have truly read, since their clandestine nature provided a less restrictive product choice.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In one case, political books were the most popular category, primarily libels and pamphlets.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Readers were more interested in sensationalist stories about criminals and political corruption than they were in political theory itself.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The second most popular category, "general works" (those books "that did not have a dominant motif and that contained something to offend almost everyone in authority"), demonstrated a high demand for generally low-brow subversive literature.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, these works never became part of literary canon and are largely forgotten today as a result.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A healthy, legal publishing industry existed throughout Europe, although established publishers and book sellers occasionally ran afoul of the law.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie*, condemned by both the King and Clement XII, nevertheless found its way into print with the help of the aforementioned Malesherbes and creative use of French censorship law.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, many works were sold without running into any legal trouble at all.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Borrowing records from libraries in England, Germany, and North America indicate that more than 70% of books borrowed were novels.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Less than 1% of the books were of a religious nature, indicating the general trend of declining religiosity.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A genre that greatly rose in importance was that of scientific literature.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Natural history in particular became increasingly popular among the upper classes.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Works of natural history include René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur's *Histoire naturelle des insectes* and Jacques Gautier d'Agoty's *La Myologie complète, ou description de tous les muscles du corps humain* (1746).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Outside Ancien Régime France, natural history was an important part of medicine and industry, encompassing the fields of botany, zoology, meteorology, hydrology, and mineralogy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Students in Enlightenment universities and academies were taught these subjects to prepare them for careers as diverse as medicine and theology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As shown by Matthew Daniel Eddy, natural history in this context was a very middle class pursuit and operated as a fertile trading zone for the interdisciplinary exchange of diverse scientific ideas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The target audience of natural history was French upper class, evidenced more by the specific discourse of the genre than by the generally high prices of its works.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Naturalists catered to upper class desire for erudition: many texts had an explicit instructive purpose.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, natural history was often a political affair.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In this way, natural history spread many of the scientific developments of the time but also provided a new source of legitimacy for the dominant class.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From this basis, naturalists could then develop their own social ideals based on their scientific works.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first scientific and literary journals were established during the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first journal, the Parisian *Journal des sçavans*, appeared in 1665.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, it was not until 1682 that periodicals began to be more widely produced.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French and Latin were the dominant languages of publication, but there was also a steady demand for material in German and Dutch.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] There was generally low demand for English publications on the continent, which was echoed by England's similar lack of desire for French works.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Languages commanding less of an international market—such as Danish, Spanish, and Portuguese—found journal success more difficult, and a more international language was used instead.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French slowly took over Latin's status as the *lingua franca* of learned circles.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This in turn gave precedence to the publishing industry in Holland, where the vast majority of these French language periodicals were produced.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Jonathan Israel called the journals the most influential cultural innovation of European intellectual culture.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They shifted the attention of the "cultivated public" away from established authorities to novelty and innovation, and instead promoted the Enlightened ideals of toleration and intellectual objectivity.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Being a source of knowledge derived from science and reason, they were an implicit critique of existing notions of universal truth monopolized by monarchies, parliaments, and religious authorities.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They also advanced Christian Enlightenment that upheld "the legitimacy of God-ordained authority"—the Bible—in which there had to be agreement between the biblical and natural theories.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although the existence of dictionaries and encyclopedias spanned into ancient times, the texts changed from defining words in a long running list to far more detailed discussions of those words in 18th-century encyclopedic dictionaries.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The works were part of an Enlightenment movement to systematize knowledge and provide education to a wider audience than the elite.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the 18th century progressed, the content of encyclopedias also changed according to readers' tastes.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Volumes tended to focus more strongly on secular affairs, particularly science and technology, rather than matters of theology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with secular matters, readers also favoured an alphabetical ordering scheme over cumbersome works arranged along thematic lines.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Encyclopedias and dictionaries also became more popular during the Enlightenment as the number of educated consumers who could afford such texts began to multiply.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the latter half of the 18th century, the number of dictionaries and encyclopedias published by decade increased from 63 between 1760 and 1769 to approximately 148 in the decade proceeding the French Revolution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with growth in numbers, dictionaries and encyclopedias also grew in length, often having multiple print runs that sometimes included in supplemented editions.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first technical dictionary was drafted by John Harris and entitled *Lexicon Technicum: Or, An Universal English Dictionary of Arts and Sciences.* Harris' book avoids theological and biographical entries and instead concentrates on science and technology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Published in 1704, the *Lexicon Technicum* was the first book to be written in English that took a methodical approach to describing mathematics and commercial arithmetic along with the physical sciences and navigation.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Other technical dictionaries followed Harris' model, including Ephraim Chambers' *Cyclopaedia* (1728), which included five editions and is a substantially larger work than Harris'.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The folio edition of the work even included foldout engravings.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Cyclopaedia* emphasized Newtonian theories, Lockean philosophy and contained thorough examinations of technologies, such as engraving, brewing, and dyeing.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In Germany, practical reference works intended for the uneducated majority became popular in the 18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Marperger Curieuses Natur-, Kunst-, Berg-, Gewerk- und Handlungs-Lexicon* (1712) explained terms that usefully described the trades and scientific and commercial education.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Jablonksi Allgemeines Lexicon* (1721) was better known than the *Handlungs-Lexicon* and underscored technical subjects rather than scientific theory.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, over five columns of text were dedicated to wine while geometry and logic were allocated only twenty-two and seventeen lines, respectively.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first edition of the *Encyclopædia Britannica* (1771) was modelled along the same lines as the German lexicons.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the prime example of reference works that systematized scientific knowledge in the Enlightenment were universal encyclopedias rather than technical dictionaries.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was the goal of universal encyclopedias to record all human knowledge in a comprehensive reference work.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The most well-known of these works is Diderot and d'Alembert's *Encyclopédie, ou dictionnaire raisonné des sciences, des arts et des métiers.* The work, which began publication in 1751, was composed of 35 volumes and over 71,000 separate entries.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A great number of the entries were dedicated to describing the sciences and crafts in detail and provided intellectuals across Europe with a high-quality survey of human knowledge.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The massive work was arranged according to a "tree of knowledge." The tree reflected the marked division between the arts and sciences, which was largely a result of the rise of empiricism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Both areas of knowledge were united by philosophy, or the trunk of the tree of knowledge.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Enlightenment's desacrilization of religion was pronounced in the tree's design, particularly where theology accounted for a peripheral branch, with black magic as a close neighbour.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the *Encyclopédie* gained popularity, it was published in quarto and octavo editions after 1777.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The quarto and octavo editions were much less expensive than previous editions, making the *Encyclopédie* more accessible to the non-elite.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Robert Darnton estimates that there were approximately 25,000 copies of the *Encyclopédie* in circulation throughout France and Europe before the French Revolution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The extensive yet affordable encyclopedia came to represent the transmission of Enlightenment and scientific education to an expanding audience.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most important developments that the Enlightenment era brought to the discipline of science was its popularization.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] An increasingly literate population seeking knowledge and education in both the arts and the sciences drove the expansion of print culture and the dissemination of scientific learning.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The new literate population was precipitated by a high rise in the availability of food; this enabled many people to rise out of poverty, and instead of paying more for food, they had money for education.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More formal works included explanations of scientific theories for individuals lacking the educational background to comprehend the original scientific text.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Newton's celebrated *Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica* was published in Latin and remained inaccessible to readers without education in the classics until Enlightenment writers began to translate and analyze the text in the vernacular.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first significant work that expressed scientific theory and knowledge expressly for the laity, in the vernacular and with the entertainment of readers in mind, was Bernard de Fontenelle's *Conversations on the Plurality of Worlds* (1686).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The book was produced specifically for women with an interest in scientific writing and inspired a variety of similar works.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These popular works were written in a discursive style, which was laid out much more clearly for the reader than the complicated articles, treatises, and books published by the academies and scientists.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Writing for a growing female audience, Francesco Algarotti published *Il Newtonianism per le dame*, which was a tremendously popular work and was translated from Italian into English by Elizabeth Carter.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A similar introduction to Newtonianism for women was produced by Henry Pemberton.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] His *A View of Sir Isaac Newton's Philosophy* was published by subscription.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Extant records of subscribers show that women from a wide range of social standings purchased the book, indicating the growing number of scientifically inclined female readers among the middling class.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, women also began producing popular scientific works.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Sarah Trimmer wrote a successful natural history textbook for children titled *The Easy Introduction to the Knowledge of Nature* (1782), which was published for many years in eleven editions.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Most work on the Enlightenment emphasizes the ideals discussed by intellectuals, rather than the actual state of education at the time.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leading educational theorists like England's John Locke and Switzerland's Jean Jacques Rousseau both emphasized the importance of shaping young minds early.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] By the late Enlightenment, there was a rising demand for a more universal approach to education, particularly after the American Revolution and the French Revolution.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The predominant educational psychology from the 1750s onward, especially in northern European countries, was associationism: the notion that the mind associates or dissociates ideas through repeated routines.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Children were taught to memorize facts through oral and graphic methods that originated during the Renaissance.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Many of the leading universities associated with Enlightenment progressive principles were located in northern Europe, with the most renowned being the universities of Leiden, Göttingen, Halle, Montpellier, Uppsala, and Edinburgh.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These universities, especially Edinburgh, produced professors whose ideas had a significant impact on Britain's North American colonies and later the American Republic.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Within the natural sciences, Edinburgh's medical school also led the way in chemistry, anatomy, and pharmacology.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In other parts of Europe, the universities and schools of France and most of Europe were bastions of traditionalism and were not hospitable to the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the major exception was the medical university at Montpellier.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The history of Academies in France during the Enlightenment begins with the Academy of Science, founded in 1666 in Paris.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was closely tied to the French state, acting as an extension of a government seriously lacking in scientists.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It helped promote and organize new disciplines and it trained new scientists.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It also contributed to the enhancement of scientists' social status, considering them to be the "most useful of all citizens." Academies demonstrate the rising interest in science along with its increasing secularization, as evidenced by the small number of clerics who were members (13%).
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of the French academies in the public sphere cannot be attributed to their membership, as although the majority of their members were bourgeois, the exclusive institution was only open to elite Parisian scholars.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They perceived themselves as "interpreters of the sciences for the people." For example, it was with this in mind that academicians took it upon themselves to disprove the popular pseudo-science of mesmerism.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The strongest contribution of the French Academies to the public sphere comes from the *concours académiques* (roughly translated as "academic contests") they sponsored throughout France.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These academic contests were perhaps the most public of any institution during the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The practice of contests dated back to the Middle Ages and was revived in the mid-17th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The subject matter had previously been generally religious and/or monarchical, featuring essays, poetry, and painting.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More importantly, the contests were open to all, and the enforced anonymity of each submission guaranteed that neither gender nor social rank would determine the judging.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, although the "vast majority" of participants belonged to the wealthier strata of society ("the liberal arts, the clergy, the judiciary and the medical profession"), there were some cases of the popular classes submitting essays and even winning.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similarly, a significant number of women participated—and won—the competitions.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Of a total of 2,300 prize competitions offered in France, women won 49—perhaps a small number by modern standards but very significant in an age in which very few women had any academic training.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, the majority of the winning entries were for poetry competitions, a genre commonly stressed in women's education.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In England, the Royal Society of London played a significant role in the public sphere and the spread of Enlightenment ideas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was founded by a group of independent scientists and given a royal charter in 1662.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The society played a large role in spreading Robert Boyle's experimental philosophy around Europe and acted as a clearinghouse for intellectual correspondence and exchange.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Boyle was "a founder of the experimental world in which scientists now live and operate" and his method based knowledge on experimentation, which had to be witnessed to provide proper empirical legitimacy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is where the Royal Society came into play: witnessing had to be a "collective act" and the Royal Society's assembly rooms were ideal locations for relatively public demonstrations.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Salons were places where *philosophes* were reunited and discussed old, actual, or new ideas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This led to salons being the birthplace of intellectual and enlightened ideas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were especially important to the spread of knowledge during the Enlightenment because they created a unique environment in which people from many different walks of life gathered and shared ideas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They were frequently criticized by nobles who feared the possibility of an environment in which class and its accompanying titles and privileges were disregarded.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Such an environment was especially intimidating to monarchs who derived much of their power from the disparity between classes of people.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] If the different classes joined together under the influence of Enlightenment thinking, they might recognize the all-encompassing oppression and abuses of their monarchs and because of the numbers of their members might be able to successfully revolt.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Monarchs also resented the idea of their subjects convening as one to discuss political matters, especially matters of foreign affairs.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rulers thought political affairs were their business only, a result of their divine right to rule.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeeshops became homes away from home for many who sought to engage in discourse with their neighbors and discuss intriguing and thought-provoking matters, from philosophy to politics.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were essential to the Enlightenment, for they were centers of free-thinking and self-discovery.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although many coffeehouse patrons were scholars, many were not.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses attracted a diverse set of people, including the educated wealthy and bourgeois as well as the lower classes.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Patrons, being doctors, lawyers, merchants, represented almost all classes, so the coffeeshop environment sparked fear in those who wanted to preserve class distinction.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most popular critiques of the coffeehouse said that it "allowed promiscuous association among people from different rungs of the social ladder, from the artisan to the aristocrat" and was therefore compared to Noah's Ark, receiving all types of animals, clean and unclean.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This unique culture served as a catalyst for journalism, when Joseph Addison and Richard Steele recognized its potential as an audience.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Together, Steele and Addison published *The Spectator (1711)*, a daily publication which aimed, through fictional narrator Mr.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Spectator, to both entertain and provoke discussion on serious philosophical matters.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first English coffeehouse opened in Oxford in 1650.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Brian Cowan said that Oxford coffeehouses developed into "penny universities," offering a locus of learning that was less formal than at structured institutions.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These penny universities occupied a significant position in Oxford academic life, as they were frequented by those consequently referred to as the *virtuosi,* who conducted their research on some of the premises.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was established in Paris in 1686, and by the 1720s there were around 400 cafés in the city.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope in particular became a center of Enlightenment, welcoming such celebrities as Voltaire and Rousseau.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was where Diderot and D'Alembert decided to create the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The cafés were one of the various "nerve centers" for *bruits publics,* public noise or rumour.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These *bruits* were allegedly a much better source of information than were the actual newspapers available at the time.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies are an example of the public sphere during the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the late 1770s, popular debating societies began to move into more "genteel" rooms, a change which helped establish a new standard of sociability.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The backdrop to these developments was "an explosion of interest in the theory and practice of public elocution." The debating societies were commercial enterprises that responded to this demand, sometimes very successfully.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Some societies welcomed from 800 to 1,200 spectators per night.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies discussed an extremely wide range of topics.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In addition to debates on religion, societies discussed issues such as politics and the role of women.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the critical subject matter of these debates did not necessarily translate into opposition to the government; the results of the debate quite frequently upheld the *status quo*.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From a historical standpoint, one of the most important features of the debating society was their openness to the public, as women attended and even participated in almost every debating society, which were likewise open to all classes providing they could pay the entrance fee.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Once inside, spectators were able to participate in a largely egalitarian form of sociability that helped spread Enlightenment ideas.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historians have debated the extent to which the secret network of Freemasonry was a main factor in the Enlightenment.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leaders of the Enlightenment included Freemasons such as Diderot, Montesquieu, Voltaire, Lessing, Pope, Horace Walpole, Robert Walpole, Mozart, Goethe, Frederick the Great, Benjamin Franklin and George Washington.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Norman Davies said Freemasonry was a powerful force on behalf of liberalism in Europe from about 1700 to the twentieth century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It expanded during the Enlightenment, reaching practically every country in Europe.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was especially attractive to powerful aristocrats and politicians as well as intellectuals, artists, and political activists.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, Freemasons comprised an international network of like-minded men, often meeting in secret in ritualistic programs at their lodges.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They promoted the ideals of the Enlightenment and helped diffuse these values across Britain, France, and other places.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry as a systematic creed with its own myths, values, and rituals originated in Scotland c.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] 1600 and spread to England and then across the Continent in the 18th century.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry was particularly prevalent in France—by 1789, there were perhaps as many as 100,000 French Masons, making Freemasonry the most popular of all Enlightenment associations.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Freemasons displayed a passion for secrecy and created new degrees and ceremonies.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similar societies, partially imitating Freemasonry, emerged in France, Germany, Sweden, and Russia.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One example was the Illuminati, founded in Bavaria in 1776, which was copied after the Freemasons, but was never part of the movement.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The name itself translates to "enlightened," chosen to reflect their original intent to promote the values of the movement.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Illuminati was an overtly political group, which most Masonic lodges decidedly were not.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Masonic lodges created a private model for public affairs.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They "reconstituted the polity and established a constitutional form of self-government, complete with constitutions and laws, elections, and representatives." In other words, the micro-society set up within the lodges constituted a normative model for society as a whole.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This was especially true on the continent: when the first lodges began to appear in the 1730s, their embodiment of British values was often seen as threatening by state authorities.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the Parisian lodge that met in the mid 1720s was composed of English Jacobite exiles.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Furthermore, freemasons across Europe explicitly linked themselves to the Enlightenment as a whole.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, in French lodges the line "As the means to be enlightened I search for the enlightened" was a part of their initiation rites.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] British lodges assigned themselves the duty to "initiate the unenlightened." This did not necessarily link lodges to the irreligious, but neither did this exclude them from the occasional heresy.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In fact, many lodges praised the Grand Architect, the masonic terminology for the deistic divine being who created a scientifically ordered universe.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Diderot discusses the link between Freemason ideals and the enlightenment in D'Alembert's Dream, exploring masonry as a way of spreading enlightenment beliefs.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historian Margaret Jacob stresses the importance of the Masons in indirectly inspiring enlightened political thought.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On the negative side, Daniel Roche contests claims that Masonry promoted egalitarianism and he argues the lodges only attracted men of similar social backgrounds.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of noble women in the French "lodges of adoption" that formed in the 1780s was largely due to the close ties shared between these lodges and aristocratic society.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The major opponent of Freemasonry was the Catholic Church so in countries with a large Catholic element, such as France, Italy, Spain, and Mexico, much of the ferocity of the political battles involve the confrontation between what Davies calls the reactionary Church and enlightened Freemasonry.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Even in France, Masons did not act as a group.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] American historians, while noting that Benjamin Franklin and George Washington were indeed active Masons, have downplayed the importance of Freemasonry in causing the American Revolution because the Masonic order was non-political and included both Patriots and their enemy the Loyalists.
[src:allendism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] At the same time, the classical art of Greece and Rome became interesting to people again, since archaeological teams discovered Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] After the February Revolution of 1917, he joined the newly formed provisional government, first as Minister of Justice, then as Minister of War, and after July as the government's second Minister-Chairman.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He was the leader of the social-democratic Trudovik faction of the Socialist Revolutionary Party.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was also a vice-chairman of the Petrograd Soviet, a position that held a sizable amount of power.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky became the prime minister of the Provisional Government, and his tenure was consumed with World War I.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Despite mass opposition to the war, Kerensky chose to continue Russia's participation.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His government cracked down on anti-war sentiment and dissent in 1917, which made his administration even more unpopular.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky remained in power until the October Revolution.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] This revolution saw the Bolsheviks create a government led by them in a coalition with the Left Socialist-Revolutionaries, to replace Kerensky's government.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky fled Russia and lived the remainder of his life in exile, mostly in Paris and New York City.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He also worked for the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, California.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He died in New York on 11 June 1970, at the age of 89.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Both the local Russian and Serbian Orthodox churches refused his body due to his Freemasonry, and because they saw him as largely responsible for the Bolshevik seizure of power.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Eventually, his body was flown to London and buried in the non-sectarian Putney Vale Cemetery.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Alexander Kerensky was born in Simbirsk (now Ulyanovsk) on the Volga river on 4 May 1881 and was the eldest son in the family.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His father, Fyodor Mikhailovich Kerensky, was a teacher and director of the local gymnasium, and was later promoted to be an inspector of public schools.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His paternal grandfather Mikhail Ivanovich served as a priest in the village of Kerenka in the Gorodishchensky district of the Penza Governorate from 1830.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The surname Kerensky comes from the name of this village.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His maternal grandfather was head of the Topographical Bureau of the Kazan Military District.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His mother, Nadezhda Aleksandrovna (née Adler), was the granddaughter of a former serf who had managed to purchase his freedom before serfdom was abolished in 1861.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He subsequently embarked upon a mercantile career, in which he prospered.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] This allowed him to move his business to Moscow, where he continued his success and became a wealthy Moscow merchant.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Members of the Kerensky and Ulyanov families were friends; Kerensky's father was the teacher of Vladimir Ulyanov (Lenin), and had even secured him acceptance into the University of Kazan.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] In 1889, when Kerensky was eight, the family moved to Tashkent, where his father had been appointed the superintendent of public schools.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky graduated with honours in 1899.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Petersburg University, where he studied history and philology.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He earned his law degree in 1904 and married Olga Lvovna Baranovskaya, the daughter of a Russian general, the same year.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky joined the Narodnik movement and worked as a legal counsel to victims of the Revolution of 1905.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] At the end of 1904, he was jailed on suspicion of belonging to a militant group.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Afterwards, he gained a reputation for his work as a defence lawyer in a number of political trials of revolutionaries.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] In 1912, Kerensky became widely known when he visited the goldfields at the Lena River and published material about the Lena massacre.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] In fact, the Socialist Revolutionary Party bought Kerensky a house, as he otherwise would not be eligible for election to the Duma, according to the Russian property laws.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] 8. stop the harassment of legal trade union organizations.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] In August, he became a significant member of the Progressive Bloc, which included several socialist parties, Mensheviks, and Liberals – but not Bolsheviks.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was an active member of the irregular Freemasonic lodge the Grand Orient of Russia's Peoples, which derived from the Grand Orient of France.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was Secretary-General of the Grand Orient of Russia's Peoples and stood down following his ascent to the government in July 1917.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He was succeeded by a Menshevik, Alexander Halpern.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] According to Kerensky, Rasputin had terrorised the empress by threatening to return to his native village.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Members of the nobility murdered Rasputin in December 1916, and he was buried near the imperial residence in Tsarskoye Selo.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Shortly after the February Revolution of 1917, Kerensky ordered soldiers to re-bury the corpse at an unmarked spot in the countryside.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] However, the truck broke down or was forced to stop because of the snow on Lesnoe Road outside of St.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] It is likely the corpse was incinerated (between 3 and 7 in the morning) in the cauldrons of the nearby boiler shop of the Saint Petersburg State Polytechnical University, including the coffin, without leaving a single trace.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] When the February Revolution broke out in 1917, Kerensky – together with Pavel Milyukov – was one of its most prominent leaders.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] As one of the Duma's most well-known speakers against the monarchy and as a lawyer and defender of many revolutionaries, Kerensky became a member of the Provisional Committee of the State Duma and was elected vice-chairman of the newly formed Petrograd Soviet.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] These two bodies, the Duma and the Petrograd Soviet, or – rather – their respective executive committees, soon became each other's antagonists on most matters except regarding the end of the tsar's autocracy.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The Petrograd Soviet grew to include 3000 to 4000 members, and their meetings could drown into a blur of lengthy speeches.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] 28 February] 1917 the executive committee of the Petrograd Soviet, or Ispolkom, formed a self-appointed committee, with (eventually) three members from each of the parties represented in the Soviet.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky became one of the members representing the Socialist Revolutionary Party (the SRs).
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] 1 March] 1917, without any consultation with the government, the Ispolkom of the Soviet issued the infamous Order No.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] 1, intended only for the 160,000-strong Petrograd garrison, but soon interpreted as applicable to all soldiers at the front.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The order stipulated that all military units should form committees like the Petrograd Soviet.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] This led to confusion and "stripping of officers' authority"; further, "Order No.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] 3" stipulated that the military was subordinate to Ispolkom in the political hierarchy.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The ideas came from a group of socialists and aimed to limit the officers' power to military affairs.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The socialist intellectuals believed the officers to be the most likely counterrevolutionary elements.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's role in these orders is unclear, but he participated in the decisions.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] But just as before the revolution he had defended many who disliked the tsar, he now saved the lives of many of the tsar's civil servants about to be lynched by mobs.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Additionally, the Duma formed an executive committee which eventually became the Russian Provisional Government.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] As there was little trust between Ispolkom and this government (and as he was about to accept the office of Attorney General in the Provisional Government), Kerensky gave a most passionate speech, not just to the Ispolkom, but to the entire Petrograd Soviet.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He then swore, as minister, never to violate democratic values, and ended his speech with the words "I cannot live without the people.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] In the moment you begin to doubt me, then kill me." The huge majority (workers and soldiers) gave him great applause, and Kerensky now became the first and *the only one* who participated in both the Provisional Government and the Ispolkom.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] As a link between Ispolkom and the Provisional Government, Kerensky stood to benefit from this position.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] After the first government crisis over Milyukov's secret note re-committing Russia to its original war-aims on 2–4 May, Kerensky became the Minister of War and the dominant figure in the newly formed socialist-liberal coalition government.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] On 10 May (Julian calendar), Kerensky started for the front and visited one division after another, urging the men to do their duty.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His speeches were impressive and convincing for the moment, but had little lasting effect.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Under Allied pressure to continue the war, he launched what became known as the Kerensky Offensive against the Austro-Hungarian/German South Army on 1 July [O.S.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] At first successful, the offensive soon met strong resistance and the Central Powers riposted with a strong counter-attack.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The Russian army retreated and suffered heavy losses, and it became clear from many incidents of desertion, sabotage, and mutiny that the army was no longer willing to attack.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Many officers scornfully referred to commander-in-chief Kerensky as the "persuader-in-chief".
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] On 2 July 1917 the Provisional Government's first coalition collapsed over the question of Ukraine's autonomy.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Following the July Days unrest in Petrograd (3–7 July [16–20 July, N.S.] 1917) and the official suppression of the Bolsheviks, Kerensky succeeded Lvov as Russia's prime minister on 21 July [O.S.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Following the Kornilov Affair, an attempted military coup d'état at the end of August, and the resignation of the other ministers, he appointed himself Supreme Commander-in-Chief, as well.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He formed a five-member Directory, which consisted of himself, Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Tereshchenko, Minister of War General Aleksandr Verkhovsky, Minister of the Navy Admiral Dmitry Verderevsky and Minister of Posts and Telegraphs Aleksei Nikitin.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He retained his post in the final coalition government in October 1917 until the Bolsheviks overthrew it on 7 November [O.S.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky faced a major challenge: three years of participation in World War had exhausted Russia, while the provisional government offered little motivation for a victory outside of continuing Russia's obligations towards its allies.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Russia's continued involvement in the war was not popular among the lower and middle classes, and especially not popular among the soldiers.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] They had all believed that Russia would stop fighting when the Provisional Government took power, and subsequently felt deceived.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Furthermore, Lenin and his Bolshevik party were promising "peace, land, and bread" under a communist system.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The Russian army, war-weary, ill-equipped, dispirited and ill-disciplined, was disintegrating, with soldiers deserting in large numbers.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] By autumn 1917, an estimated two million men had unofficially left the army.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The dilemma of whether to withdraw was a great one, and Kerensky's inconsistent and impractical policies further destabilised the army and the country at large.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Furthermore, Kerensky adopted a policy that isolated the right-wing conservatives and nationalists, both democratic and monarchist-oriented.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His philosophy of "no enemies to the left" greatly empowered the Bolsheviks and gave them a free hand, allowing them to take over the military arm or "voyenka" (Russian: Военка) of the Petrograd and Moscow Soviets.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] During the Kornilov Affair, Kerensky had distributed arms to the Petrograd workers, and by November most of these armed workers had gone over to the Bolsheviks.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] 25–26 October] 1917, the Bolsheviks launched the second Russian revolution of the year.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's government in Petrograd had almost no support in the city.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The Bolsheviks overthrew the government rapidly by seizing governmental buildings and the Winter Palace.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky escaped the Bolsheviks and fled to Pskov, where he rallied some loyal troops for an attempt to re-take the city.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His troops managed to capture Tsarskoye Selo but were beaten the next day at Pulkovo.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky narrowly escaped, and he spent the next few weeks in hiding before fleeing the country, eventually arriving in France.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] During the Russian Civil War, he supported neither side, as he opposed both the Bolshevik regime and the White Movement.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Meanwhile, viewed by Woodrow Wilson as the spokesman for Russian democracy, he strongly influenced Wilson on Russian matters.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was married to Olga Lvovna Baranovskaya and they had two sons, Oleg (1905–1984) and Gleb (1907–1990), who both went on to become engineers.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's grandson (also named Oleg), according to the Internet Movie Database, played his grandfather's role in the 1981 film *Reds*.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky and Olga were divorced in 1939 soon after he settled in Paris, and in the same year, while visiting the United States, he met and secretly married Lydia Ellen "Nell" Tritton (1899–1946), the Australian former journalist who had become his press secretary and translator.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The marriage took place in Martins Creek, Pennsylvania.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] When Germany invaded France in 1940, they emigrated to the United States.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] During the Nazi invasion of the Soviet Union, Kerensky expressed his willingness to support the Russian people's defense against Hitler, despite his long-standing opposition to the Soviet regime.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] In a published article, he criticized both Lenin and Stalin but stated that the survival of Russia as a nation took precedence over political differences.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] When his wife Nell became terminally ill in 1945, Kerensky travelled with her to Brisbane, Australia, and lived there with her family.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] She suffered a stroke in February 1946, and he remained there until her death on 10 April 1946.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky then returned to the United States, where he spent the rest of his life.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He wrote and broadcast extensively on Russian politics and history.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] His last public lecture was delivered at Kalamazoo College in Kalamazoo, Michigan, in October 1967.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky died of arteriosclerotic heart disease at St.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Luke's Hospital in New York City on 11 June 1970 at the age of 89, after being initially admitted for injuries sustained from a fall.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] He was one of the last surviving major participants in the turbulent events of 1917.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] The local Russian Orthodox Churches in New York City refused to grant Kerensky burial rites because of his association with Freemasonry, and because they saw him as largely responsible for the Bolsheviks' seizure of power.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] A Serbian Orthodox Church also refused burial rites.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's body was flown to London, where his two sons resided; he was buried at the non-denominational Putney Vale Cemetery.
[src:allendism/alexander-kerensky] Papers of the Kerensky family are held at the Cadbury Research Library, University of Birmingham.
[src:allendism/allendism] Allende's doctrine spoke of structurally reforming the country while at the same time trying to reach agreements with the Christian Democratic Party, the Confederation of Democracy, and the business sectors so as not to increase the internal and social tension that the country was experiencing.
[src:allendism/allendism] The Communist Party, which favored these measures, spoke of "moving forward by consolidating".
[src:allendism/allendism] During the coup, Pinochet ordered the immediate assassination of Carlos Altamirano, considering him a possible factor in armed resistance.
[src:allendism/allendism] After the so-called “socialist renewal”, in which the exiles of the UP in Europe embraced and internalized the institutional framework and social democracy as ideological bases, Allendism adopted a more institutional and conciliatory character concerning the reforms raised by the same current.
[src:allendism/allendism] Currently, experts define Allendism as a feeling of nostalgia for the Popular Unity period, without necessarily wanting to restore or retry the reforms made during that time.
[src:allendism/allendism] After the Chilean transition to democracy, Allendism as a political ideology was welcomed by different left-wing political parties.
[src:allendism/allendism] On December 9, 1991, the leftist political coalition *Movimiento de Izquierda Democrática Allendista* was formed.
[src:allendism/allendism] It comprised the Communist Party, the Communist Party (Proletarian Action), MAPU, the Revolutionary Left Movement, and the Christian Left.
[src:allendism/allendism] It was directed by Pedro Vuskovic, former socialist militant and Minister of Economy during the government of Allende, and also included other left-wing personalities among its main figures, such as priest Rafael Maroto and deputy Mario Palestro.
[src:allendism/allendism] It participated in the 1992 municipal elections, achieving the election of 35 councilors and the appointment of Jorge Soria as mayor of the commune of Iquique.
[src:allendism/allendism] In the 1993 presidential election, it supported the candidacy of priest Eugenio Pizarro and presented candidates for the National Congress in the parliamentary elections of that same year.
[src:allendism/allendism] In the latter, it participated under the Left Democratic Alternative, officially registered with the Electoral Service on July 14.
[src:allendism/allendism] The coalition formally dissolved on May 10, 1993.
[src:allendism/allendism] On September 28, 2019, Jorge Arrate and Ernesto Águila founded the political party Socialist Platform.
[src:allendism/allendism] In its beginnings, it was a member of Apruebo Dignidad, and since February 2023, it has been from the Broad Front.
[src:allendism/allendism] The *Movimiento del Socialismo Allendista* emerged in 2021.
[src:allendism/allendism] Its main leader is Esteban Silva Cuadra, who left the Socialist Party.
[src:allendism/allendism] It was also a member of the *Allendistas por Jadue* commando, whose objective was to "ensure the victory" of the communist politician Daniel Jadue in the presidential primaries on July 18, and rescue Allende's legacy.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The **anarchist movement in Chile** emerged from European immigrants, followers of Mikhail Bakunin affiliated with the International Workingmen's Association, who contacted Manuel Chinchilla, a Spaniard living in Iquique.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Their influence could be perceived at first within the labour unions of typographers, painters, builders and sailors.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] During the first decades of the 20th century, anarchism had a significant influence on the labour movement and intellectual circles of Chile.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Some of the most prominent Chilean anarchists were: the poet Carlos Pezoa Véliz, the professor Dr.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] At the moment, anarchist groups are experiencing a comeback in Chile through various student collectives, affinity groups, community and cultural centres, and squatting.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] During the French Revolution of 1848, a number of Chilean radicals visited Paris, where they became acquainted with the mutualism of Pierre-Joseph Proudhon and the Christian socialism of Félicité de La Mennais.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Upon their return to Chile in 1850, Francisco Bilbao and Santiago Arcos established the Equality Society (Spanish: *Sociedad de la Igualidad*, SI), a mutual aid society which was suppressed before the end of the year by the Chilean authorities.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Other mutualist societies were founded throughout the 1850s, culminating in 1862 with the formation of The Union (Spanish: *La Union*), which became highly influential among artisans in many Chilean cities, providing free health care and organising workshops for the unemployed.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The mutualist movement quickly formed a counterculture in Chile, believing that capitalism could be replaced peacefully through institutions of dual power.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Anarchist propaganda began circulating in Chile around 1880, consisting of literary works arriving from Spain and Argentina.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The first libertarian newspaper, *El Oprimido,*was published in 1893 in Valparaíso, followed by others such as: *El Ácrata*, *La Luz*, *La Revuelta*, *La Batalla*, *El Surco*, *Acción Directa* and others.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] *La Batalla*was published continually for a longer period of time, between 1912 and 1926.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] There were also various newspapers published by general unions with anarchist tendencies, such as: *El Siglo XX*, *La Imprenta* (typographers) and *El Marítimo* in Antofagasta (sailors).
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] As far as anarchist literature was concerned, the publishing house *Editorial Lux*distinguished itself by printing books by Chilean and European anarchists such as Manuel Márquez and José Domingo Gómez Rojas.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Among other notable militants were the typographer Enrique Arenas from Iquique, founder of a number of anarchist newspapers, as well as Luis Olea, Alejandro Magno Espinosa and Alejandro Escobar y Carballo, the driving force behind several general unions.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] General unions engaged in conflict with the older and newer benefit societies, which had been in existence since the mid-nineteenth century, and which they considered incapable of defending the interests of the working class.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The newspaper *El Faro* criticised the old benefit societies, branding them as "the mutualist mummies that have been eternally vegetating without any sort of practical profit, or the economical development of which they should be responsible as the developers of all kinds of social wealth".
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] This context of a growing working-class movement set the basis for the emergence of co-operatives, which adopted a strictly defensive position despite their anarcho-syndicalist inspiration.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The first co-operative was founded by dockworkers in Iquique on 1 May 1900, and later ones emerged in Antofagasta, Chañaral and Copiapó.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In 1904 the first National Convention of Co-operatives was organised in Santiago, with the participation of 20 000 members from 15 organisations.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The defensive character of these organisations meant that most co-operatives were under the control of socialists and Marxists, particularly members of the Democrat Party.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Many of these went on to form the Workers' Federation of Chile (FOCH).
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] One of the first conflicts triggered by the anarchists was "the Great Boatmen Strike" of 1890, which took place in Iquique, Antofagasta, Valparaíso, Concepción and other smaller ports.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] A strike broke out in Valparaíso in 1903 at the South American Steamboat Company (CSV), which was suppressed violently, causing the workers to react by setting fire to the company's headquarters.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In 1905, a spontaneous workers' movement took place in Santiago, encouraged by the anarchists.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The movement started as a consequence of an unjustified repression by the police of a rally protesting against taxes on imported meat.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The fierce repression and clashes with the police resulted in the deaths of around 200 workers.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The indignation of the workers grew stronger and stronger, and most of the labour unions went on general strike.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The government declared a state of siege and called upon the army to suppress the movement.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The crowds attempted to take over the governmental palace, and even though they did not succeed, the city remained under their control.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The response of the government was to increase the repression and to persecute the revolutionary anarchists and syndicalists who were the leaders of the movement.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] However, anarchist activity was still on the rise.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The anarchist newspaper *El Alba* condemned the acts in an edition released in October 1905: "The people have been assassinated with rage and malice by the young horde of the bourgeoisie.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] More than 500 citizens have been murdered vilely and cowardly, and more than 1500 were injured".
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In 1906 a general strike was declared in Antofagasta, run by the railroad workers.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] On 21 December 1907, the strike aimed at improving the pay of the saltpetre (nitrate) miners in Iquique ended in a massacre carried out by the authorities, known as the Santa María School massacre.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] It was there that the army fired into the crowd that had gathered in Santa María square, killing around 3000 people, among them workers, women, and children.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Spanish anarchist Antonio Ramón attempted to assassinate Roberto Silva Renard in revenge.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] After the Russian Revolution (which was regarded with distrust by most anarchists from the very beginning), the divide between anarchists and Marxists deepened.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Their cohabitation within general unions came to an end, and the moderate and reformist socialists took over the Workers' Federation of Chile (FOCH).
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] 5 September 1924 the civic and military coup d'état was repudiated by the Chilean left wing.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Nevertheless, the restorative military movement of January 1925 was supported by the socialist and communist forces.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The anarchists and the organizations who exercised their influence decided to stay back and not trust the military.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In 1925 there was a rent strike in Santiago.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The government decided to form a "Housing Board" to solve conflicts between tenants and owners, an arrangement that was supported by the communists.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The anarcho-syndicalists rejected this arrangement, which they believed had as an objective to divide the strike movement.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The anarchists founded a new worker's organization the same year.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The Chilean Workers' Regional Federation (known by its abbreviation in Spanish FORCH), affiliated to the International Workers' Association (AIT): taking as a model the Argentinean Regional Worker's Association (FORA).
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In January 1927 a general strike took place in Santiago and Valparaíso.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] A month after general Ibáñez demoted president Arturo Alessandri with a new coup d'état.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The 1930s crisis hit the population hard which continued to strike in the streets.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In response, the dictatorship suppressed the workers' organizations and disarticulated them almost completely.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Following the end of the dictatorship in 1931, the communists and socialists founded the Worker's Confederation of Chile (CTCH).
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The anarchists created their own General Worker's Confederation (CGT).
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The syndicalist prominence had remained in the hands of the reformist syndicalism of the socialists, communists, and the Christian Democrats.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] 12927, dictated on the "Inner Security of the State", amended on several occasions and prevailing to the present day, sanctions any act of insurrectionist or revolutionary nature.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] After the coup d'état of general Augusto Pinochet, a repressive wave was triggered against all the left wing, including the few individual anarchists who still existed.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In 1975, the Committee of Defense of Human rights (CODEH) was reactivated by Clotario Blest and Ernesto Miranda, which would become of vital importance for those persecuted by the dictatorship.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The anarchist affiliation during the dictatorship did not have an organic character, limiting itself to the work of some individuals that contributed to the formation of resistance groups against the dictatorship, especially in universities and population scope.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Anarchism as a social movement vanished during those years.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The Anarchist Communist Unification Congress (CUAC) was formed in 1999, lasting a few years.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Anarchism as a practice in Chile today is mostly present in the organisation of counter movements and culture.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Diverse and decentralised collectives and individuals try to disseminate anarchist ideas and practices through squatting, cultural activities, strikes, and protests.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Several anarchist and libertarian groups initiated a series of congresses in 2010, involving the Libertarian Students Front (FEL) and three organizations that would converge in the Libertarian Communist Federation (FCL).
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In addition, a group called the Libertarian Communist Organization (OCL) continued the work of CUAC.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In the year 2012 the First Anarchist Book Fair in Santiago took place; it was organized again in 2013, 2014 and 2015.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In 2013, with the election of Melissa Sepúlveda as president, anarchists took leadership of the Student Federation of the University of Chile.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In contrast, another current, more critical of electoral politics, launched the Libertarian Communist Congress that met between the late 2013 and early 2016.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Solidaridad, originally named Solidarity, Libertarian Communist Federation, was formed from this second current.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Since 2019, the Anarchist Federation Santiago started organising an anarchist platform in the country's capital.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Further, the Mapuche conflict and anti-government protests, most recently the 2019 uprising Estallido social, form part of contemporary representations of anarchist practices, however sometimes without direct reference to anarchist schools of thought.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] However, the rejection of the current government institutions and the legitimacy of the current constitution, combined with claims for and practices of autonomy and self-organisation form a central pillar of these movements and are inspired by libertarian anarchist principles.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Protesting formations like Primera Línea, referred to as "clans" without a central authority, act according to anarchist principles.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] Similarly, the Mapuche conflict as a struggle for political, economic, and territorial autonomy is supported by other anarchist movements worldwide.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The Mapuche struggle, by anarchist principles, fundamentally objects to the state and questions the legitimacy of the Chilean Republic as the successor to the colonial sovereign.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] One of the first victims in the clashes with the police after the return to democracy was anarchist dance student Claudia López Benaiges, who died due to the action of the state security forces during the disturbances of September 1998.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In March 2008, young anarchist Jhonny Cariqueo Yánez died as a result of the beating suffered on 29 March (Young Combatant's Day) while he was under arrest by the Carabineros de Chile in Santiago.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] That December, another Anarchist and supporter of the Mapuche cause, Juan "Orangu" Cruz Magna, 28, from Santiago, was shot in the neck by strangers when he was spending time at the Mapuche community of Temucuicui.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In May 2009, anarchist Mauricio Morales died in Santiago Centro when the bomb that he was carrying at his back went off near the Gendarmerie School.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In August 2010, in the so-called "Bombs Case", the squatter house *Sacco y Vanzetti* was raided and 14 people were arrested, including anarchists, anti-authoritarians and Marxists.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] After eight months in prison and several months of probation, all of those charged were declared innocent after a long trial that culminated in the Chilean Supreme Court.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In October 2012, an appeal was rejected that sought to annul the ruling that acquitted the accused.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In 2012, young Anarchist Luciano Pitronello was sentenced to six years of probation.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] The process had begun with his arrest under charges of terrorism for installing a bomb at a bank of Santander branch, and ended with him being charged for handling of explosives and the use a false patent.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In November 2013 some young anarchists acquitted in the "Bombs Case" were arrested in Spain accused of installing explosive devices at Cathedral-Basilica of Our Lady of the Pillar injuring a woman.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] They were found guilty of "Terrorist damages" and "terrorist injuries" and sentenced to 12 years in prison.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] At least 200 artifacts have exploded in Chile since 2005.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] This has led to the formulation of charges against some thirty anarchists.
[src:allendism/anarchism-in-chile] In the vast majority of cases, these devices have been detonated to cause damage to the property of law enforcement and security forces, banks or transnational corporations and, in some cases, they have injured and even killed people.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Having served as Member of Parliament (MP) for South Gloucestershire from 1950 to 1955, Crosland returned to Parliament for Great Grimsby (1959–1977).
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] During Harold Wilson's governments of 1964–1970 he served as Economic Secretary to the Treasury (1964), then Minister of State for Economic Affairs (1964–1965).
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Entering the Cabinet as Secretary of State for Education and Science (1965–1967), he led the Labour campaign to replace grammar schools with comprehensive schools that did not use the eleven-plus for the selection of pupils.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He later served as President of the Board of Trade (1967–1969), then Secretary of State for Local Government and Regional Planning (1969–1970).
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] When Labour returned to power he served as Secretary of State for the Environment (1974–1976) and briefly as Foreign Secretary (1976–1977).
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] In that role he promoted détente with the Soviet Union.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He died suddenly in February 1977 of a cerebral haemorrhage, aged 58.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland was born at St Leonards-on-Sea in East Sussex.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] His father, Joseph Beardsall Crosland, was a senior official at the War Office, and his mother, Jessie Raven, was an academic.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Both of his parents were members of the Plymouth Brethren.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] His maternal grandfather was Frederick Edward Raven (1837–1903), founder of the Raven Exclusive Brethren and secretary of the Royal Naval College, Greenwich.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland later rejected his family's religion.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He grew up in north London and was educated at Highgate School and at Trinity College, Oxford, obtaining a second class honours degree in Classical Moderations in Greek and Latin Literature.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] In the spring of 1941, Crosland was commissioned in the Royal Welch Fusiliers, and in late 1942 he joined (as part of the 6th (Royal Welch) Parachute Battalion) the 2nd Parachute Brigade, which was part of the 1st Airborne Division.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] In September 1943, he participated in the landings at Taranto, Operation Slapstick.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland had his first direct experience of combat in Italy in December .
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He then became an intelligence officer gathering information for several months in the front line about troop movements at the Battle of Monte Cassino, and was also briefly involved in the Allied invasion of southern France as part of Operation Rugby in August 1944.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] After the war, Crosland returned to Oxford University and obtained first class honours in Philosophy, Politics and Economics, which he studied in 12 months; he also became President of the Oxford Union.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He then became a university don at Oxford, tutoring in Economics.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Notable people he taught at Oxford included Tony Benn, Norris McWhirter and Ross McWhirter.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland, who had been talent-spotted by Hugh Dalton, was chosen as a Labour candidate in December 1949 to fight the next general election.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He entered Parliament at the February 1950 general election, being returned for the South Gloucestershire constituency.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He held that seat until the 1955 general election, when he was defeated at Southampton Test.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland returned to the House of Commons at the 1959 general election when he was elected for Grimsby, which he would represent for the rest of his life.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He was, like Roy Jenkins and Denis Healey, a friend and protégé of Hugh Gaitskell, and together they were regarded as the "modernisers" of their day.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] From June 1960, Crosland played an important part in the establishment of the Campaign for Democratic Socialism, a right-wing grassroots group within the Labour Party, created, in part, as a response to the debates around the Left's advocacy of unilateral nuclear disarmament and Clause IV.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] However, Crosland was against Gaitskell's attempts to change Clause 4.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Even though they were from the same wing of the party, the thought of the Labour Party being led by the volatile George Brown appalled Crosland, but he also was a critic of Harold Wilson for his apparent lack of principles.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Just over two years earlier Wilson had challenged Gaitskell for the party leadership.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland nominated and voted for James Callaghan in the leadership contest caused by Gaitskell's death on 18 January 1963.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He rationalised his decision to back Callaghan on the basis that "We have to choose between a crook [Harold Wilson] and a drunk [George Brown]".
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] However, Callaghan was eliminated after obtaining 41 votes, the margin in votes between Wilson and Brown in the final ballot.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] With Callaghan eliminated, Crosland's second wife wrote in her 1982 biography, he voted for George Brown in the second ballot, although with zero enthusiasm, and with little interest about the result, as he was opposed to both of the candidates now standing for the party leadership.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Wilson won by 144 votes to Brown's 103 on 14 February 1963.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Although critical of Harold Wilson, and angry with him for his 1960 challenge to Gaitskell for the party leadership, Crosland respected him as a political operator.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Under Wilson, Crosland was first appointed Brown's deputy in October 1964.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] In November 1964 Crosland and Brown told Wilson and Callaghan that ruling out devaluation was a mistake in the face of the economic crisis then under way.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] However, Crosland was not Brown's deputy for long.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] On 22 January 1965, Wilson appointed Crosland Secretary of State for Education and Science.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] The ongoing campaign for Comprehensive schools in England and Wales gained a major boost with Circular 10/65, which as a statute rather than a Government Bill was controversial at the time, although a government motion in favour of the policy had been passed in January 1965.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland's policy gained approval from local government; by 1979 over 90% of pupils were in comprehensive schools.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] In her biography published in 1982, Susan Crosland said her husband had told her "If it's the last thing I do, I'm going to destroy every fucking grammar school in England.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Another major educational change was that presaged by his speech at Woolwich Polytechnic (now Greenwich University) establishing a 'binary system' of higher education, in which universities would be joined by polytechnic institutions which concentrated on high-level vocational skills.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] In October 1966, a committee of ministers in the Labour government decided to increase university fees for overseas students.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Two months later Crosland announced their decision which treated Commonwealth students for the first time as if they were foreign.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Widespread protests, which erupted immediately, soon united a large number of influential people from across a wide spectrum from left-wing militant students to mildly conservative vice-chancellors.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland subsequently served as President of the Board of Trade from September 1967 to October 1969.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He was deeply disappointed not to have been made Chancellor of the Exchequer after the November 1967 cabinet reshuffle which followed the devaluation of the pound.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Then he became Secretary of State for Local Government and Regional Planning until the election defeat of June 1970.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland was seen as a leader and intellectual guru of the "right wing" or "social democratic" wing of the Labour Party in the 1970s.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] In April 1972, he stood for the deputy leadership of the party after Roy Jenkins resigned.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He polled 61 votes of the Parliamentary Labour Party and was eliminated in the first round.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] The contest was eventually won by Edward Short, who defeated Michael Foot.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland was embarrassed by the national press in January 1973 when it emerged he had been given a silver coffee pot donated by disgraced corrupt architect John Poulson when opening a school in Bradford in January 1966.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] It later transpired that the pot was only silver-plated, and therefore of trivial value.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] After Labour's return to power in March 1974, Crosland became Secretary of State for the Environment.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He was instrumental in changing Transport policy on British Rail to be a higher fare fast intercity passenger service rather than its previous role as a general freight common carrier.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He contested the leadership in March 1976 following Wilson's resignation, but polled only 17 votes and finished bottom of the poll.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] After his elimination, he switched his support to the eventual winner James Callaghan, who duly rewarded Crosland by appointing him Foreign Secretary on 8 April 1976.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland's time as foreign secretary was dominated by the Third Cod War and relations with Rhodesia.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland once quipped to his wife that "when I pop off and they cut open my heart, on it will be engraved 'fish' and 'Rhodesia'".
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Early in his life Crosland had numerous gay affairs, including allegedly with Roy Jenkins.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland benefited from the patronage of Hugh Dalton, who, in 1951, wrote to Richard Crossman: "Thinking of Tony, with all his youth and beauty and gaiety and charm...
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] I am more fond of that young man than I can put into words." According to Nicholas Davenport, Dalton's unrequited feelings for Crosland became an embarrassing joke within the Labour Party.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland married Hilary Sarson in November 1952, divorcing after five years, though the marriage had effectively ended after a year.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Crosland had numerous affairs with other women.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] He remarried on 7 February 1964 to Susan Catling, an American from Baltimore resident in London whom he had met in 1956, and, in contrast to his first marriage, this was very happy and contented.
[src:allendism/anthony-crosland] Susan Crosland was a successful journalist and writer.
